WEBVTT

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:29.280
Part 1

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.060
Story of the Door

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:38.660
Mr. Utterson, the lawyer, was a man of a rugged countenance that was never lighted

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:45.280
by a smile, cold, scanty, and embarrassed in discourse, backward in sentiment, lean,

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:50.100
long, dusty, dreary, and yet somehow lovable.

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:57.360
At friendly meetings, and when the wine was to his taste, something eminently human beaconed

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:02.980
from his eye, something indeed which never found its way into his talk, but which spoke

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:09.900
not only in these silent symbols of the after-dinner face, but more often and loudly in the acts

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:10.920
of his life.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:17.160
He was austere with himself, drank gin when he was alone to mortify a taste for vintages,

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:22.680
and though he enjoyed the theatre, had not crossed the doors of one for twenty years.

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:31.240
But he had an approved tolerance for others, sometimes wondering, almost with envy, at

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:37.700
the high pressure of spirits involved in their misdeeds, and in any extremity inclined to

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:39.880
help rather than to reprove.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:47.420
I inclined to Cain's heresy, he used to say, quietly, I let my brother go to the devil

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:48.520
in his own way.

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:55.200
In this character it was frequently his fortune to be the last reputable acquaintance and

00:01:55.200 --> 00:02:02.380
the last good influence in the lives of down-going men, and to such as these, so long as they

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:07.720
came about his chambers, he never marked a shade of change in his demeanour.

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:15.240
No doubt the feat was easy to Mr. Utterson, for he was undemonstrative at the best, and

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:19.600
Even his friendship seemed to be founded in a similar catholicity of good nature.

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:26.260
It is the mark of a modest man to accept his friendly circle ready-made from the hands

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:29.920
of opportunity, and that was the lawyer's way.

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:35.420
His friends were those of his own blood, or those whom he had known the longest.

00:02:36.040 --> 00:02:43.400
His affections, like ivy, were the growth of time, they implied no aptness in the object.

00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:50.640
Hence, no doubt, the bond that united him to Mr. Richard Enfield, his distant kinsman,

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:52.920
the well-known man about town.

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:59.120
It was a nut to crack for many what these two could see in each other, or what subject

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:00.580
they could find in common.

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:06.760
It was reported by those who encountered them in their Sunday walks, that they said nothing,

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:12.500
look singularly dull, and would hail with obvious relief the appearance of a friend.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:18.840
For all that, the two men put the greatest store by these excursions, counted them the

00:03:18.840 --> 00:03:24.700
chief jewel of each week, and not only set aside occasions of pleasure, but even resisted

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:29.040
the cause of business, that they might enjoy them uninterrupted.

00:03:30.200 --> 00:03:35.900
It chanced on one of these rambles that their way led them down a by-street in a busy quarter

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:36.500
of London.

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:43.620
The street was small, and what is called quiet, but it drove a thriving trade on the weekdays.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:49.740
The inhabitants were all doing well, it seemed, and all emulously hoping to do better still,

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:55.300
and laying out the surplus of their grains in coquetry, so that the sharp fronts stood

00:03:55.300 --> 00:04:01.040
along that thoroughfare with an air of invitation, like rows of smiling saleswomen.

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:07.660
Even on Sunday, when it veiled its more florid charms, and lay comparatively empty of passage,

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:15.320
the street shone out in contrast to its dingy neighborhood, like a fire in a forest, and

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:21.340
with its freshly painted shutters, well-polished brasses, and general cleanliness and gaiety

00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:26.200
of note, instantly caught and pleased the eye of the passenger.

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:34.100
Two doors from one corner, on the left hand going east, the line was broken by the entry

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:40.800
of a court, and just at that point a certain sinister block of building thrust forward

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:42.360
its gable on the street.

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:49.600
It was two stories high, showed no window, nothing but a door on the lower story and

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:55.820
a blind forehead of discolored wall on the upper, and bore in every feature the marks

00:04:55.820 --> 00:04:58.720
of prolonged and sordid negligence.

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:05.700
The door, which was equipped with neither bell nor knocker, was blistered and disdained.

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:12.140
Tramps slouched into the recess and struck matches on the panels, children kept shop

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:18.360
under the steps, the schoolboy had tried his knife on the moldings, and for close on a

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:24.960
generation no one had appeared to drive away these random visitors, or to repair their

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:26.700
savages.

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:32.440
Mr. Enfield and the lawyer were on the other side of the by-street, but when they came

00:05:32.440 --> 00:05:36.960
abreast of the entry, the former lifted up his cane and pointed.

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:43.740
"'Did you ever remark that door?' he asked, and when his companion had replied in the

00:05:43.740 --> 00:05:50.680
affirmative, "'It is connected in my mind,' added he, with a very odd story.'

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:55.080
"'Indeed?' said Mr. Utterson, with a slight change of voice.

00:05:55.680 --> 00:05:58.020
"'And what was that?'

00:05:58.020 --> 00:06:01.880
"'Well, it was this way,' returned Mr. Enfield.

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:07.540
"'I was coming home from some place at the end of the world about three o'clock of a

00:06:07.540 --> 00:06:13.400
black winter morning, and my way lay through a part of town where there was literally nothing

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:19.100
to be seen but lamps, street after street, and all the folks asleep.

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:26.240
Street after street, all lighted up as if for a procession, and all as empty as a church,

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:33.100
till at last I got into that state of mind when a man listens and listens, and begins

00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:34.740
to long for the sight of a policeman.

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:49.080
All at once I saw two figures, one a little man who was stumping along eastward at a good

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:50.700
down a cross street.

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:57.940
Well, sir, the two ran into one another naturally enough at the corner, and then came the horrible

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:04.120
part of the thing, for the man trampled calmly over the child's body and left her screaming

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:04.980
on the ground.

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:09.700
It sounds nothing to hear, but it was hellish to see.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:14.820
It wasn't like a man, it was like some damned juggernaut.

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:22.160
I gave a few, hello, took to my heels, collared my gentleman, and brought him back to where

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.180
there was already quite a group about the screaming child.

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:33.460
He was perfectly cool and made no resistance, but gave me one look so ugly that it brought

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:35.880
out the sweat on me like running.

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:42.480
The people who turned out were the girl's own family, and pretty soon the doctor for

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:45.220
whom she had been sent put in his appearance.

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:51.740
Well, the child was not much the worse, more frightened, according to the saw-bones, and

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:57.780
there you might have supposed would be an end to it, but there was one curious circumstance.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:05.080
I had taken a loathing to my gentleman at first sight, so had the child's family, which

00:08:05.080 --> 00:08:09.760
was only natural, but the doctor's case was what struck me.

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:15.700
He was the usual cut-and-dry apothecary of no particular age and colour, with a strong

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:19.940
Edinburgh accent, and about as emotional as a bagpipe.

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:24.340
Well, sir, he was like the rest of us.

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:31.700
Every time he looked at my prisoner I saw that saw-bones turn sick and white with desire

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:32.700
to kill him.

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:39.500
I knew what was in his mind just as he knew what was in mine, and killing being out of

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:42.040
question, we did the next best.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:48.480
We told the man we could and would make such a scandal out of this as should make his name

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:51.000
stink from one end of London to the other.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:57.260
If he had any friends or any credit, we undertook that he should lose them.

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:03.260
And all the time, as we were pitching it in red hot, we were keeping the women off him

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:06.960
as best we could, for they were as wild as harpies.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:13.940
I never saw a circle of such hateful faces, and there was the man in the middle, with

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:16.820
a kind of black, sneering coolness.

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:22.660
Frightened too, I could see that, but carrying it off, sir, really likes Satan.

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:29.740
If you choose to make capital out of this accident, said he, I am naturally helpless.

00:09:30.580 --> 00:09:35.040
No gentleman but wishes to avoid a scene, says he.

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:37.040
Name your figure.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.300
Well, we screwed him up to a hundred pounds for the child's family.

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:47.460
He would have clearly liked to stick out, but there was something about the lot of us

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:50.940
that meant mischief, and at last he struck.

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:54.680
The next thing was to get the money.

00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:00.240
And where do you think he carried us but to that place with the door?

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:06.860
Whipped out a key, went in, and presently came back with the matter of ten pounds in

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:14.760
gold and a check for the balance on coots, drawn payable to bearer, and signed with a

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:20.640
name that I can't mention, though it's one of the points of my story, but it was a name

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:23.280
at least very well known and often printed.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:29.640
The figure was stiff, but the signature was good for more than that if it was only genuine.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:36.200
I took the liberty of pointing out to my gentleman that the whole business looked apocryphal,

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:41.700
and that a man does not, in real life, walk into a cellar door at four in the morning

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:45.840
and come out with another man's check for close upon a hundred pounds.

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:49.920
But he was quite easy and sneering.

00:10:50.620 --> 00:10:57.800
Set your mind at rest, says he, I will stay with you till the banks open and cash the

00:10:57.800 --> 00:10:58.560
check myself.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:07.120
So we all set off, the doctor and the child's father and our friend and myself, and passed

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:12.920
the rest of the night in my chambers, and the next day, when we had breakfasted, went

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:14.600
in a body to the bank.

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:20.420
I gave in the check myself, and said I had every reason to believe it was a forgery.

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:24.520
Not a bit of it, the check was genuine.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.900
Tot-tot! said Utterson.

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:31.600
I see you feel as I do, said Mr. Enfield.

00:11:32.220 --> 00:11:39.860
Yes, it's a bad story, for my man was a fellow that nobody could have to do with, a really

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:45.540
damnable man, and the person that drew the check is the very pink of the proprieties.

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:52.520
Celebrated too, and, what makes it worse, one of your fellows who do what they call

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:53.180
good.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:59.860
Blackmail, I suppose, an honest man paying through the nose for some of the capers of

00:11:59.860 --> 00:12:00.460
his youth.

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:07.280
Blackmail House is what I call the place with the door in consequence, though even that,

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:14.780
you know, is far from explaining all, he added, and with the words fell into a vein of musing.

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:23.040
From this he was recalled by Mr. Utterson asking rather suddenly, and you don't know

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:25.340
if the drawer of the check lives there.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:32.920
A likely place isn't it, returned Mr. Enfield, but I happen to have noticed his address,

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:35.720
he lives in some square or other.

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:40.660
And you never asked about the place with the door, said Mr. Utterson.

00:12:41.600 --> 00:12:45.660
No, sir, I had a delicacy, was the reply.

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:52.920
I feel very strongly about putting questions, it partakes too much of the style of the day

00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:53.600
of judgment.

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:57.800
You start a question, and it's like starting a stone.

00:12:58.540 --> 00:13:04.900
You sit quietly on the top of a hill, and away the stone goes, starting others, and

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:10.760
presently some bland old bird, the last you would have thought of, is knocked on the head

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:15.040
in his own back garden, and the family have to change their name.

00:13:15.740 --> 00:13:18.640
No, sir, I make it a rule of mine.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:22.720
The more it looks like queer streets, the less I ask.

00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:26.800
A very good rule too, said the lawyer.

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:32.500
But I have studied the place for myself, continued Mr. Enfield.

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:35.340
It seems scarcely a house.

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:42.280
There is no other door, and nobody goes in or out of that one, but once in a great while

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:43.860
the gentleman of my adventure.

00:13:43.860 --> 00:13:49.500
There are three windows looking on the court on the first floor, none below.

00:13:50.040 --> 00:13:53.280
The windows are always shut, but they're clean.

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:59.280
And then there is a chimney which is generally smoking, so somebody must live there.

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:06.060
And yet it's not so sure, for the buildings are so packed together about the court that

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:09.340
it's hard to say where one ends and another begins.

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:15.600
The pair walked on again for a while in silence, and then—

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:20.860
Enfield, said Mr. Utterson, that's a good rule of yours.

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:24.940
Yes, I think it is, returned Enfield.

00:14:26.140 --> 00:14:32.280
But for all that, continued the lawyer, there is one point I want to ask.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:36.840
I want to ask the name of that man who walked over the child.

00:14:37.620 --> 00:14:43.120
Well, said Mr. Enfield, I can't see what harm it would do.

00:14:43.660 --> 00:14:46.420
It was a man of the name of Hyde.

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:52.460
Hmm, said Utterson, what sort of a man is he to see?

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:55.820
He is not easy to describe.

00:14:56.520 --> 00:15:02.560
There is something wrong with his appearance, something displeasing, something downright

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:03.460
detestable.

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:09.200
I never saw a man I so disliked, and yet I scarce know why.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:16.140
He must be deformed somewhere, he gives a strong feeling of deformity, although I can't

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:17.420
specify the point.

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:23.380
He's an extraordinary-looking man, and yet I really can name nothing out of the way.

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:27.680
No, sir, I can make no hand of it.

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:34.880
I can't describe him, and it's not want of memory, for I declare I can see him this moment.

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:42.420
Mr. Utterson again walked some way in silence, and obviously under a weight of consideration.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:45.520
You are sure he used a key?

00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:47.500
He inquired at last.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.900
My dear sir, began Enfield, surprised out of himself.

00:15:53.620 --> 00:15:59.040
Yes, I know, said Utterson, I know it must seem strange.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:05.980
The fact is, if I do not ask you the name of the other party, it's because I know it

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:06.540
already.

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:10.580
You see, Richard, your tale has gone home.

00:16:11.140 --> 00:16:15.600
If you have been inexact in any point, you had better correct it.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:21.900
I think you might have warned me, returned the other with a touch of solidness.

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:26.400
But I have been pedantically exact, as you call it.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:30.700
The fellow had a key, and what's more, he has it still.

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:33.780
I saw him use it not a week ago.

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:41.820
Mr. Utterson sighed deeply, but said never a word, and the young man presently resumed.

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:46.500
Here is another lesson to say nothing, said he.

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:49.480
I am ashamed of my long tongue.

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:53.980
Let us make a bargain never to refer to this again.

00:16:55.160 --> 00:16:57.860
With all my heart, said the lawyer.

00:16:58.180 --> 00:17:00.820
I shake hands on that, Richard.

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:06.760
Search for Mr. Hyde

00:17:07.620 --> 00:17:13.600
That evening Mr. Utterson came home to his bachelor house in sombre spirits, and sat

00:17:13.600 --> 00:17:15.460
down to dinner without relish.

00:17:16.140 --> 00:17:23.400
It was his custom of a Sunday, when this meal was over, to sit close by the fire, a volume

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:28.900
of some dry divinity on his reading-desk, until the clock of the neighbouring church

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:34.420
rang out the hour of twelve, when he would go soberly and gratefully to bed.

00:17:35.240 --> 00:17:41.080
On this night, however, as soon as the cloth was taken away, he took up a candle and went

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:42.420
into his business-room.

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:49.200
There he opened his safe, took from the most private part of it a document endorsed on

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:56.280
the envelope as Dr. Jekyll's Will, and sat down with a clouded brow to study its contents.

00:17:57.360 --> 00:18:03.380
The Will was holograph, for Mr. Utterson, though he took charge of it now it was made,

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:07.260
had refused to lend the least assistance in the making of it.

00:18:07.810 --> 00:18:17.460
It provided not only that in case of the decease of Henry Jekyll, MD, DCL, LLD, FRS, etc.,

00:18:17.460 --> 00:18:22.720
all his possessions were to pass into the hands of his friend and benefactor Edward

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:29.740
Hyde, but that in case of Dr. Jekyll's disappearance or unexplained absence for any period exceeding

00:18:29.740 --> 00:18:36.220
three calendar months, the sad Edward Hyde should step into the said Henry Jekyll's shoes

00:18:36.220 --> 00:18:42.060
without further delay, and free from any burden or obligation beyond the payment of

00:18:42.060 --> 00:18:45.160
a few small sums to the members of the doctor's household.

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:50.400
This document had long been the lawyer's eyesore.

00:18:50.740 --> 00:18:56.980
It offended him both as a lawyer and as a lover of the sane and customary sides of life,

00:18:57.580 --> 00:19:04.160
to whom the fanciful was the immodest, and hitherto it was his ignorance of Mr. Hyde

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:05.900
that had swelled his indignation.

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:09.880
Now by a sudden turn it was his knowledge.

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:15.880
It was already bad enough when the name was but a name of which he could learn no more.

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:22.440
It was worse when it began to be closed upon with detestable attributes, and out of the

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:28.860
shifting insubstantial mists that had so long baffled his eye, there leaped up the sudden

00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:31.460
definite presentment of a fiend.

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:40.300
I thought it was madness, he said, as he replaced the obnoxious paper in the safe, and now I

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:42.400
begin to fear it is disgrace.

00:19:43.500 --> 00:19:48.920
With that he blew out his candle, put on a greatcoat, and set forth in the direction

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:55.580
of Cavendish Square, the citadel of medicine, where his friend the great Dr. Lanyon had

00:19:55.580 --> 00:19:58.300
his house and received his crowding patients.

00:19:59.020 --> 00:20:02.720
If anyone knows, it will be Lanyon, he had thought.

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:06.860
The solemn butler knew and welcomed him.

00:20:07.140 --> 00:20:12.420
He was subjected to no stage of delay, but ushered direct from the door to the dining

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:16.000
room, where Dr. Lanyon sat alone over his wine.

00:20:16.780 --> 00:20:23.020
This was a hearty, healthy, dapper red-faced gentleman, with a shock of hair prematurely

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:25.860
white, and a boisterous and decided manner.

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:32.820
At sight of Mr. Utterson, he sprang up from his chair and welcomed him with both hands.

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:39.780
The geniality, as was the way of the man, was somewhat theatrical to the eye, but it

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:41.760
deposed on genuine feeling.

00:20:42.340 --> 00:20:48.560
For these two were old friends, old mates both at school and college, both thorough

00:20:48.560 --> 00:20:55.220
respectors of themselves and of each other, and what does not always follow, men who thoroughly

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:57.060
enjoyed each other's company.

00:20:58.140 --> 00:21:04.120
After a little rambling talk, the lawyer led up to the subject which so disagreeably

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:05.700
preoccupied his mind.

00:21:07.220 --> 00:21:14.500
Um, I suppose, Lanyon, said he, you and I must be the two oldest friends that Henry

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:15.600
Jekyll has.

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:23.340
I wish the friends were younger, chuckled Dr. Lanyon, but I suppose we are, and what

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:23.880
of that?

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:25.920
I see little of him now.

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:31.360
Indeed, said Utterson, I thought you had a bond of common interest.

00:21:31.860 --> 00:21:38.100
We had, was the reply, but it is more than ten years since Henry Jekyll became too

00:21:38.100 --> 00:21:39.320
fanciful for me.

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:46.040
He began to go wrong, wrong in mind, and, and though, of course, I continue to take

00:21:46.040 --> 00:21:52.220
an interest in him from old sakes' sake, as they say, I see, and I have seen,

00:21:52.220 --> 00:21:54.080
devilishly little of the man.

00:21:54.640 --> 00:22:01.380
Such unscientific balderdash, added the doctor, flushing suddenly purple, would have

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:03.660
estranged Damon and Pytheas.

00:22:04.340 --> 00:22:09.400
This little spirit of temper was somewhat of a relief to Mr. Utterson.

00:22:10.100 --> 00:22:15.660
They have only differed on some point of science, he thought, and being a man of no

00:22:16.220 --> 00:22:23.280
passions, except in the matter of conveyancing, he even added, it is nothing worse than that.

00:22:24.340 --> 00:22:29.560
He gave his friend a few seconds to recover his composure, and then approached the question

00:22:29.560 --> 00:22:30.840
he had come to put.

00:22:31.500 --> 00:22:37.480
Did you ever come across a protege of his, one Hyde?

00:22:38.020 --> 00:22:38.840
He asked.

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:40.080
Hyde?

00:22:40.700 --> 00:22:41.580
Repeated Lanyon.

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:44.720
No, never heard of him.

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:45.980
Since my time.

00:22:46.800 --> 00:22:51.380
That was the amount of information that the lawyer carried back with him to the great

00:22:51.380 --> 00:22:57.840
dark bed on which he tossed to and fro, until the small hours of the morning began to grow large.

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:04.280
It was a night of little ease to his toiling mind, toiling in mere darkness and besieged by

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:04.880
questions.

00:23:05.920 --> 00:23:14.700
Six o'clock struck on the bells of the church that was so conveniently near to Mr. Utterson's

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:15.260
problem.

00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:22.940
Hitherto it had touched him on the intellectual side alone, but now his imagination also was

00:23:22.940 --> 00:23:29.380
engaged, or rather enslaved, and as he lay and tossed in the gross darkness of the night

00:23:29.380 --> 00:23:36.140
and the curtained room, Mr. Enfield's tale went by before his mind in a scroll of lighted

00:23:36.140 --> 00:23:36.620
pictures.

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:44.160
He would be aware of the great field of lamps of a nocturnal city, then of the figure of a man

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:52.200
walking swiftly, and then of a child running from the doctors, and then these met, and that human

00:23:52.200 --> 00:23:58.060
juggernaut trod the child down and passed on, regardless of her screams.

00:23:58.820 --> 00:24:05.100
Or else he would see a room in a rich house, where his friend lay asleep, dreaming and

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:11.460
smiling at his dreams, and then the door of that room would be opened, the curtains of the bed

00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:20.160
plucked apart, the sleeper recalled, and lo, there would stand by his side a figure to whom power was

00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:25.460
given, and even at that dead hour he must rise and do its bidding.

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:33.720
The figure in these two phases haunted the lawyer all night, and if at any time he dozed over,

00:24:34.140 --> 00:24:40.200
it was but to see it glide more stealthily through sleeping houses, or move the more swiftly,

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:46.820
and still the more swiftly, even to dizziness, through wider labyrinths of lamp-lighted city,

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:51.960
and at every street corner crush a child and leave for screaming.

00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:57.140
And still the figure had no face by which he might know it.

00:24:57.860 --> 00:25:03.560
Even in his dreams it had no face, or one that baffled him and melted before his eyes,

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:09.060
and thus it was that there sprang up, and grew a pace in the lawyer's mind,

00:25:09.060 --> 00:25:16.400
a singularly strong, almost an inordinate, curiosity to behold the features of the real

00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:22.960
Mr. Hyde. If he could but once set eyes on him, he thought the mystery would lighten,

00:25:23.020 --> 00:25:28.900
and perhaps roll altogether away, as was the habit of mysterious things when well examined.

00:25:29.500 --> 00:25:36.120
He might see a reason for his friend's strange preference, or bondage, call it which you please,

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:42.640
and even for the startling claws of the will. At least it would be a face worth seeing,

00:25:43.140 --> 00:25:50.020
the face of a man who was without bowels of mercy, a face which had but to show itself

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:56.400
to raise up in the mind of the unimpressionable Enfield a spirit of enduring hatred.

00:25:57.160 --> 00:26:02.360
From that time forward Mr. Utterson began to haunt the door in the by-street of shops.

00:26:02.360 --> 00:26:08.220
In the morning before office hours, at noon when business was plenty and time scarce,

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:16.220
at night under the face of the fogged city moon, by all lights and all hours of solitude or concourse

00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:19.940
the lawyer was to be found on his chosen post.

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:27.400
If he be Mr. Hyde, he had thought, I shall be Mr. Seek.

00:26:28.620 --> 00:26:36.620
And at last his patience was rewarded. It was a fine, dry night. Frost in the air,

00:26:36.820 --> 00:26:42.200
the streets as clean as a ballroom floor, the lamps unshaken by any wind,

00:26:42.680 --> 00:26:49.140
drawing a regular pattern of light and shadow. By ten o'clock, when the shops were closed,

00:26:49.560 --> 00:26:55.100
the by-street was very solitary, and in spite of the low growl of London from all round,

00:26:55.100 --> 00:27:02.460
very silent. Small sounds carried far. Domestic sounds out of the houses were clearly audible

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:08.140
on either side of the roadway, and the rumour of the approach of any passenger preceded him

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:15.620
by a long time. Mr. Utterson had been some minutes at his post when he was aware of an odd

00:27:15.620 --> 00:27:22.660
light footstep drawing near. In the course of his nightly patrols he had long grown accustomed to

00:27:22.660 --> 00:27:28.280
quaint effect with which the footfalls of a single person, while he still is a great way off,

00:27:28.600 --> 00:27:35.020
suddenly sprang out distinct from the vast hum and clatter of the city. Yet his attention had

00:27:35.020 --> 00:27:41.940
never before been so sharply and decisively arrested, and it was with a strong superstitious

00:27:41.940 --> 00:27:49.440
prevision of success that he withdrew into the entry of the court. The steps drew swiftly

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:54.160
nearer, and swelled out suddenly louder as they turned the end of the street.

00:27:54.900 --> 00:28:01.680
The lawyer, looking forth from the entry, could soon see what manner of man he had to deal with.

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:07.560
He was small and very plainly dressed, and the look of him, even at that distance,

00:28:07.940 --> 00:28:14.180
went somehow strongly against the watch's inclination. But he made straight for the

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:20.860
crossing the roadway to save time, and as he came he drew a key from his pocket like

00:28:20.860 --> 00:28:27.700
one approaching home. Mr. Utterson stepped out and touched him on the shoulder as he passed.

00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:34.320
Mr. Hyde, I think. Mr. Hyde shrank back with a hissing intake of the breath,

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:40.100
but his fear was only momentary, and though he did not look the lawyer in the face,

00:28:40.100 --> 00:28:42.300
he answered coolly enough.

00:28:43.160 --> 00:28:46.000
That is my name. What do you want?

00:28:47.340 --> 00:28:53.760
I see you are going in, returned the lawyer. I am an old friend of Dr. Jekyll's,

00:28:53.940 --> 00:28:57.740
Mr. Utterson of Gaunt Street. You must have heard of my name,

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:02.240
and meeting you so conveniently, I thought you might admit me.

00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:09.960
You will not find Dr. Jekyll. He is from home, replied Mr. Hyde, blowing in the key.

00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:13.680
And then suddenly, but still without looking up,

00:29:13.900 --> 00:29:16.660
How do you know me? he asked.

00:29:18.020 --> 00:29:22.200
On your side, said Mr. Utterson, will you do me a favour?

00:29:22.840 --> 00:29:26.880
With pleasure, replied the other. What shall it be?

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:32.260
Will you let me see your face? asked the lawyer.

00:29:33.340 --> 00:29:38.880
Mr. Hyde appeared to hesitate, and then, as if upon some sudden reflection,

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:45.620
fronted about with an air of defiance, and the pair stared at each other pretty fixedly

00:29:45.620 --> 00:29:53.000
for a few seconds. Now I shall know you again, said Mr. Utterson. It may be useful.

00:29:54.500 --> 00:30:01.740
Yes, returned Mr. Hyde. It is as well we have met, and apropos,

00:30:01.860 --> 00:30:07.500
you should have my address, and he gave a number of a street in Soho.

00:30:08.380 --> 00:30:14.040
Good God! thought Mr. Utterson. Can he too have been thinking of the will?

00:30:15.160 --> 00:30:20.780
But he kept his feelings to himself, and only granted an acknowledgement of the address.

00:30:21.900 --> 00:30:26.320
And now, said the other, how did you know me?

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:31.360
By description, was the reply. Whose description?

00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:35.840
We have common friends, said Mr. Utterson.

00:30:36.560 --> 00:30:42.740
Common friends, echoed Mr. Hyde a little hoarsely. Who are they?

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.740
Jackal, for instance, said the lawyer.

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:52.420
He never told you, cried Mr. Hyde, and with a flush of anger,

00:30:52.900 --> 00:30:55.920
I did not think you would have lied.

00:30:56.700 --> 00:31:00.860
Come, said Mr. Utterson, that is not fitting language.

00:31:01.740 --> 00:31:07.020
The other snarled aloud into a savage laugh, and in the next moment,

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:12.860
with extraordinary quickness, he had unlocked the door and disappeared into the house.

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:19.280
The lawyer stood awhile when Mr. Hyde had left him, the picture of disquietude.

00:31:20.220 --> 00:31:22.640
Then he began slowly to mount the street,

00:31:23.220 --> 00:31:28.540
passing every step or two, and putting his head to his brow like a man in mental perplexity.

00:31:29.280 --> 00:31:36.060
The problem he was thus debating as he walked was one of a class that is rarely solved.

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:43.000
Mr. Hyde was pale and dwarfish. He gave an impression of deformity without any

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:49.960
nameable malformation. He had a displeasing smile, he had borne himself to the lawyer with a sort of

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:56.620
murderous mixture of timidity and boldness, and he spoke with a husky, whispering, and somewhat

00:31:56.620 --> 00:32:04.440
broken voice. All of these were points against him, but not all of these together could explain

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:11.540
the hitherto unknown disgust, loathing, and fear with which Mr. Utterson regarded him.

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:16.360
There must be something else, said the perplexed gentleman.

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:20.560
There is something more, if I could find a name for it.

00:32:20.560 --> 00:32:28.260
God bless me, the man seems hardly human. Something troglodytic, shall we say.

00:32:28.640 --> 00:32:36.280
Or can it be the old story of Dr. Fell? Or is it the mere radiance of a foul soul that

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:45.680
thus transpires through and transfigures its clay continent? The last, I think. For, oh my

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:53.480
poor old Harry Jekyll, if ever I read Satan's signature upon a face, it is on that of your new

00:32:53.480 --> 00:33:01.240
friend. Round the corner from the By Street there was a square of ancient, handsome houses,

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:08.480
now for the most part decayed from their high estate, and let in flats and chambers to all

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:15.220
sorts and conditions of men, map engravers, architects, shady lawyers, and the agents of

00:33:15.220 --> 00:33:22.880
secure enterprises. One house, however, second from the corner, was still occupied entire,

00:33:23.240 --> 00:33:29.260
and at the door of this, which wore a great air of wealth and comfort, though it was now plunged

00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:36.760
in darkness except for the fan-light, Mr. Utterson stopped and knocked. A well-dressed elderly

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:44.440
servant opened the door. Is Dr. Jekyll at home, Poole? asked the lawyer. I will see,

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:51.540
Mr. Utterson, said Poole, admitting the visitor as he spoke, into a large low-roofed comfortable

00:33:51.540 --> 00:33:58.020
hall, paved with flags, warmed, after the fashion of a country house, by a bright open fire,

00:33:58.620 --> 00:34:04.940
and furnished with costly cabinets of oak. Will you wait here by the fire, sir,

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:11.800
or shall I give you a light in the dining-room? Here, thank you, said the lawyer, and he drew

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:19.880
near and leaned on the tall fender. This hall, in which he was now left alone, was a pet fancy of

00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:26.100
his friend the doctors, and Utterson himself was wont to speak of it as the pleasantest room in

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:33.280
London. But to-night there was a shudder in his blood, and the face of Hyde sat heavy on his

00:34:34.010 --> 00:34:42.560
He felt, what was rare with him, a nausea and distaste of life, and in the gloom of his spirit

00:34:42.560 --> 00:34:48.280
he seemed to read a menace in the flickering of the fire-lights on the polished cabinets

00:34:48.280 --> 00:34:56.940
and the uneasy starting of the shadow on the roof. He was ashamed of his relief when Poole presently

00:34:56.940 --> 00:35:00.040
returned to announce that Dr. Jekyll was gone out.

00:35:00.480 --> 00:35:08.180
I saw Mr. Hyde go in by the old dissecting-room, Poole, he said. Is that right, when Dr. Jekyll

00:35:08.180 --> 00:35:15.920
is from home? Quite right, Mr. Utterson, sir, replied the servant. Mr. Hyde has a key.

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:21.500
Your master seems to repose a great deal of trust in that young man, Poole,

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:23.620
resumed the other amusingly.

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:30.120
Yes, sir, he does indeed, said Poole. We all have orders to obey him.

00:35:30.860 --> 00:35:35.560
I do not think I ever met Mr. Hyde, asked Utterson.

00:35:36.180 --> 00:35:44.720
Oh dear no, sir, he never dines here, replied the butler. Indeed we see very little of him on this

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:48.680
side of the house. He mostly comes and goes by the laboratory.

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:51.820
Well, good night, Poole.

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:54.420
Good night, Mr. Utterson.

00:35:55.640 --> 00:35:59.520
And the lawyer set out homeward with a very heavy heart.

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:07.340
Poor Harry Jekyll, he thought. My mind misgives me he is in deep waters.

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:12.840
He was wild when he was young, a long while ago to be sure,

00:36:12.840 --> 00:36:16.600
but in the law of God there is no statute of limitations.

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:25.060
Ay, it must be that. The ghost of some old sin, the cancer of some concealed disgrace,

00:36:25.640 --> 00:36:33.060
punishment coming, payday cloud-o, years after memory has forgotten and self-love condoned the

00:36:33.060 --> 00:36:41.300
fault. And the lawyer, scared by the thought, brooded a while on his own past, groping in all

00:36:41.300 --> 00:36:47.840
corners of memory, lest by chance some jack in the box of an old iniquity should leap to light

00:36:47.840 --> 00:36:54.740
there. His past was fairly blameless. Few men could read the roles of their life with less

00:36:54.740 --> 00:37:01.100
apprehension. Yet he was humbled to the dust by the many ill things he had done,

00:37:01.700 --> 00:37:07.980
and raised up again into sober and fearful gratitude by the many he had come so near to doing,

00:37:07.980 --> 00:37:15.780
yet avoided. And then, by a return on his former subject, he conceived a spark of hope.

00:37:16.440 --> 00:37:24.360
This master-hide, if he were studied, thought he, must have secrets of his own, black secrets by

00:37:24.360 --> 00:37:30.040
the look of him, secrets compared to which poor Jekyll's worst would be like sunshine.

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:39.480
But things cannot continue as they are. It turns me cold to think of this creature stealing like a

00:37:39.480 --> 00:37:48.180
thief to Harry's bedside. Poor Harry, what awakening! And the danger of it, for if this hide

00:37:48.180 --> 00:37:57.680
suspects the existence of the will, he may grow impatient to inherit. I must put my shoulders to

00:37:57.680 --> 00:38:05.760
wheel. If Jekyll will but let me, he added, if Jekyll will only let me. For once more,

00:38:05.980 --> 00:38:13.640
he saw before his mind's eye, as clear as transparency, the strange clauses of the will.

00:38:16.940 --> 00:38:19.760
Doctor Jekyll was quite at ease.

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:27.600
A fortnight later, by excellent good fortune, the doctor gave one of his pleasant dinners

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:34.980
to some five or six old cronies, all intelligent reputable men, and all judges of good wine.

00:38:35.720 --> 00:38:40.900
And Mr. Utterson so contrived that he remained behind after the others had departed.

00:38:41.680 --> 00:38:47.040
This was no new arrangement, but a thing that had befallen many scores of times.

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:54.680
Where Utterson was liked, he was liked well. Hosts loved to detain the dry lawyer when the

00:38:54.680 --> 00:39:00.400
light-hearted and loose-tongued had already their foot on the threshold. They liked to sit a while

00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:06.600
in his unobtrusive company, practicing for solitude, sobering their minds in the man's

00:39:06.600 --> 00:39:13.920
rich silence after the expense and strain of gaiety. To this rule Dr. Jekyll was no exception,

00:39:13.920 --> 00:39:21.440
and as he now sat on the opposite side of the fire, a large well-made smooth-faced man of fifty,

00:39:22.060 --> 00:39:27.320
with something of a stylish caste perhaps, but every mark of capacity and kindness,

00:39:28.140 --> 00:39:34.780
you could see by his looks that he cherished for Mr. Utterson a sincere and warm affection.

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:41.200
I have been wanting to speak to you, Jekyll," began the latter.

00:39:41.380 --> 00:39:43.740
You know that will of yours?

00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:49.780
A close observer might have gathered that the topic was distasteful,

00:39:50.120 --> 00:39:52.820
but the doctor carried it off gaily.

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:59.600
My poor Utterson, said he, you are unfortunate in such a client.

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:06.780
I never saw a man so distressed as you were by my will, unless it were that hide-bound

00:40:06.780 --> 00:40:14.460
pedant Lanyon, at what he called my scientific heresies. Oh, I know he's a good fellow,

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:20.120
you needn't frown, an excellent fellow, and I always mean to see more of him.

00:40:20.520 --> 00:40:27.500
But a hide-bound pedant for all that, an ignorant, blatant pedant, I was never more

00:40:27.500 --> 00:40:29.940
disappointed in any man than Lanyon.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:37.580
You know I never approved of it, pursued Utterson, ruthlessly disregarding the fresh topic.

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:39.120
My will?

00:40:40.180 --> 00:40:47.460
Yes, certainly I know that, said the doctor, a trifle sharply. You have told me so.

00:40:48.480 --> 00:40:54.800
Well, I tell you so again, continued the lawyer. I have been learning something of young hide.

00:40:55.380 --> 00:41:02.700
The large handsome face of Dr. Juckle grew pale to the very lips, and there came a blackness

00:41:02.700 --> 00:41:11.860
about his eyes. I do not care to hear more, said he. This is a matter I thought we had agreed to

00:41:11.860 --> 00:41:22.080
drop. What I heard was abominable, said Utterson. It can make no change. You do not understand my

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:29.400
position, returned the doctor with a certain incoherency of manner. I am painfully situated,

00:41:29.620 --> 00:41:38.240
Utterson. My position is a very strange—a very strange one. It is one of those affairs that cannot

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:51.420
be mended by talking. Juckle, said Utterson, you know me. I am a man to be trusted. Make a clean

00:41:51.420 --> 00:41:53.040
I can get you out of it.

00:41:53.820 --> 00:42:02.660
My good Utterson, said the doctor, this is very good of you, this is downright good of you,

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:10.760
and I cannot find words to thank you in. I believe you fully. I would trust you before

00:42:10.760 --> 00:42:19.840
any man alive, I before myself, if I could make the choice. But indeed it isn't what you fancy.

00:42:19.840 --> 00:42:27.880
It's not as bad as that, and just to put your good heart at rest, I will tell you one thing.

00:42:28.620 --> 00:42:36.620
The moment I choose, I can be rid of Mr. Hyde. I give you my hand upon it,

00:42:36.980 --> 00:42:43.760
and I thank you again and again. And I will just add one little word, Utterson,

00:42:43.760 --> 00:42:53.160
that I'm sure you'll take in good part. This is a private matter, and I beg of you to let it sleep.

00:42:54.160 --> 00:42:57.440
Utterson reflected a little, looking in the fire.

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:04.780
I have no doubt you are perfectly right, he said at last, getting to his feet.

00:43:05.660 --> 00:43:12.140
Well, but since you have touched upon this business, and for the last time, I hope,

00:43:12.140 --> 00:43:17.900
continued the doctor, there is one point I should like you to understand.

00:43:18.560 --> 00:43:26.320
I have really a very great interest in poor Hyde. I know you have seen him, he told me so,

00:43:26.460 --> 00:43:35.620
and I fear he was rude. But I do sincerely take a great, a very great interest in that young man.

00:43:35.620 --> 00:43:42.560
And if I am taken away, Utterson, I wish you to promise me that you will bear with him

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:50.640
and get his rights for him. I think you would, if you knew all, and it would be a weight off my mind

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:57.140
if you would promise. I can't pretend that I shall ever like him, said the lawyer.

00:43:57.140 --> 00:44:05.800
I don't ask that, pleaded Jackal, laying his hand upon the other's arm. I only ask for justice.

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:12.580
I only ask you to help him, for my sake, when I am no longer here.

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:16.740
Utterson heaved an irrepressible sigh.

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:22.100
Well, said he, I promise.

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:26.980
End of part one.

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:57.420
Part 2 of The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde by Robert Louis Stevenson.

00:44:59.560 --> 00:45:03.180
THE CARILL MURDER CASE

00:45:03.180 --> 00:45:11.060
Nearly a year later, in the month of October, London was startled by a crime of singular ferocity,

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:14.940
and rendered all the more notable by the high position of the victim.

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:22.600
The details were few and startling. A maidservant, living alone in a house not far from the river,

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:28.960
had gone upstairs to bed about eleven. Although a fog rolled over the city in small hours,

00:45:28.960 --> 00:45:34.520
the early part of the night was cloudless, and the lane, which the maid's window overlooked,

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:42.700
was brilliantly lit by the full moon. It seems she was romantically given, for she sat down

00:45:42.700 --> 00:45:48.940
upon her box, which stood immediately under the window, and fell into a dream of musing.

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:54.480
Never, she used to say, with streaming tears when she narrated that experience,

00:45:54.480 --> 00:46:00.420
never had she felt more at peace with all men, nor thought more kindly of the world.

00:46:01.500 --> 00:46:07.560
And as she so sat, she became aware of an aged, beautiful gentleman with white hair,

00:46:07.960 --> 00:46:14.360
drawing near along the lane, and advancing to meet him another and very small gentleman,

00:46:14.740 --> 00:46:20.700
to whom at first she paid less attention. When they had come within speech,

00:46:20.700 --> 00:46:27.540
which was just under the maid's eyes, the older man bowed, and accosted the other with a very

00:46:27.540 --> 00:46:34.100
pretty manner of politeness. It did not seem as if the subject of his address were of great importance.

00:46:34.780 --> 00:46:40.360
Indeed, from his pointing, it sometimes appeared as if he were only inquiring his way.

00:46:41.120 --> 00:46:50.680
But the moon shone on his face as he spoke, and the girl was pleased to watch it. It seemed to

00:46:50.680 --> 00:46:57.420
be of great disposition, yet with something high, too, as of a well-founded self-esteem.

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:05.900
Presently her eye wandered to the other, and she was surprised to recognize in him a certain Mr.

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:12.180
Hyde, who had once visited her master, and for whom she had conceived a dislike.

00:47:13.380 --> 00:47:20.580
He had in his hand a heavy cane with which he was trifling, but he answered never a word.

00:47:20.680 --> 00:47:24.780
And seemed to listen with an ill-contained impatience.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:32.420
And then, all of a sudden, he broke out in a great flame of anger, stamping with his feet,

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:38.740
brandishing the cane, and carrying on, as the maid described it, like a madman.

00:47:39.480 --> 00:47:45.260
The old gentleman took a step back, with the air of one very much surprised and a trifle hurt,

00:47:45.260 --> 00:47:53.180
and at that Mr. Hyde broke out of all bounds, and clubbed him to the earth. And next moment,

00:47:53.500 --> 00:48:00.260
with ape-like fury, he was trampling his victim under foot, and hailing down a storm of blows,

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:06.200
under which the bones were audibly shattered, and the body jumped upon the roadway.

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:11.580
At the horror of these sights and sounds, the maid fainted.

00:48:13.200 --> 00:48:20.220
It was two o'clock, when she came to herself, and called the police. The murderer was gone long ago,

00:48:20.660 --> 00:48:27.260
but there lay his victim in the middle of the lane, incredibly mangled. The stick with which

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:33.600
the deed had been done, although it was of some rare and very tough and heavy wood, had broken in

00:48:33.600 --> 00:48:39.900
the middle under the stress of this insensate cruelty, and one splintered half had rolled into

00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:45.220
neighbouring gutter. The other, without doubt, had been carried away by the murderer.

00:48:46.580 --> 00:48:54.300
A purse and gold watch were found upon the victim, but no cards or papers, except a sealed and stamped

00:48:54.300 --> 00:49:00.900
envelope, which he had been probably carrying to the post, and which bore the name and address

00:49:00.900 --> 00:49:07.960
of Mr. Utterson. This was brought to the lawyer the next morning, before he was out of bed,

00:49:07.960 --> 00:49:14.780
and he had no sooner seen it and been told the circumstances than he shot out a solemn lip.

00:49:15.700 --> 00:49:22.100
I shall say nothing till I have seen the body, said he. This may be very serious.

00:49:22.840 --> 00:49:29.800
Have the kindness to wait while I dress. And with the same grave countenance he hurried through his

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:36.880
breakfast and drove to the police station, whither the body had been carried. As soon as he came into

00:49:36.880 --> 00:49:38.940
cell, he nodded.

00:49:39.720 --> 00:49:47.920
Yes, said he, I recognize him. I am sorry to say that this is Sir Danvers' crew.

00:49:49.220 --> 00:49:54.140
Good God, sir! exclaimed the officer. Is it possible?

00:49:55.480 --> 00:49:59.840
And the next moment his eye lighted up with professional ambition.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:07.660
This will make a deal of noise, he said, and perhaps you can help us to the man.

00:50:08.760 --> 00:50:15.440
And he briefly narrated what the maid had seen, and showed the broken stick. Mr. Utterson had

00:50:15.440 --> 00:50:22.360
already quailed at the name of Hyde, but when the stick was laid before him he could doubt no longer.

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:29.680
Broken and battered as it was, he recognized it for one that he had himself presented many

00:50:29.680 --> 00:50:32.580
years before to Henry Jekyll.

00:50:33.900 --> 00:50:41.300
Is this Mr. Hyde a person of small stature? he inquired. A particularly small and particularly

00:50:41.300 --> 00:50:48.060
wicked looking is what the maid calls him, said the officer. Mr. Utterson reflected,

00:50:48.640 --> 00:50:57.420
and then, raising his head, if you will come with me in my cab, he said, I think I can take you to

00:50:57.420 --> 00:50:58.280
his house.

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:08.160
It was by this time about nine in the morning, and the first fog of the season. A great chocolate

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:13.980
covered pall lowered over heaven, but the wind was continually charging and routing these

00:51:13.980 --> 00:51:20.320
embattled vapors, so that as the cab crawled from street to street, Mr. Utterson beheld a marvelous

00:51:20.320 --> 00:51:27.100
number of degrees and hues of twilight. For here it would be dark like the back end of evening,

00:51:27.420 --> 00:51:33.940
and there would be a glow of a rich lurid brown like the light of some strange conflagration,

00:51:34.520 --> 00:51:41.160
and here, for a moment, the fog would be quite broken up, and a haggard shaft of daylight would

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:48.980
glance in between the swirling wreaths. The dismal quarter of Soho, seen under these changing

00:51:48.980 --> 00:51:55.660
glimpses, with its muddy ways and slatternly passengers, and its lamps, which had never been

00:51:55.660 --> 00:52:00.820
extinguished or had been kindled afresh to combat this mournful reinvasion of darkness,

00:52:01.520 --> 00:52:06.760
seemed, in the lawyer's eyes, like a district of some city in a nightmare.

00:52:07.820 --> 00:52:13.640
The thoughts of his mind besides were of the gloomiest dye, and when he glanced at the

00:52:13.640 --> 00:52:19.300
companion of his drive, he was conscious of some touch of that terror of the law and the

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:23.840
law's officers, which may at times assail the most honest.

00:52:25.660 --> 00:52:32.620
As the cab drew up before the address indicated, the fog lifted a little, and showed him a dingy

00:52:32.620 --> 00:52:39.420
street, a gin palace, a low French eating-house, a shop for the retail of penny numbers and

00:52:39.420 --> 00:52:46.220
tuppany salads, many ragged children huddled in the doorways, and many women of many different

00:52:46.220 --> 00:52:54.020
nationalities passing out, key in hand, to have a morning glass. And the next moment the fog

00:52:54.020 --> 00:53:01.220
settled down again upon that part, as brown as umber, and cut him off from his blaggardly

00:53:01.220 --> 00:53:10.380
surroundings. This was the home of Henry Jekyll's favourite, of a man who was heir to a quarter of a

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:19.940
million sterling. An ivory-faced and silvery-haired old woman opened the door. She had an evil face,

00:53:19.940 --> 00:53:28.160
smoothed by hypocrisy, but her manners were excellent. Yes, she said, this was Mr. Hyde's,

00:53:28.160 --> 00:53:33.940
but he was not at home. He had been in that night very late, but he had gone away again

00:53:33.940 --> 00:53:39.560
in less than an hour. There was nothing strange in that, his habits were very irregular,

00:53:39.920 --> 00:53:46.780
and he was often absent. For instance, it was nearly two months since she had seen him till yesterday.

00:53:48.100 --> 00:53:55.000
Very well then, we wish to see his rooms, said the lawyer, and when the woman began to declare

00:53:55.000 --> 00:54:03.900
it was impossible, I had better tell you who this person is, he added. This is Inspector Newcomen

00:54:03.900 --> 00:54:10.880
of Scotland Yard. A flash of odious joy appeared upon the woman's face.

00:54:10.880 --> 00:54:16.740
Ah! said she, he is in trouble. What has he done?

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:21.140
Mr. Utterson and the inspector exchanged glances.

00:54:22.080 --> 00:54:28.680
He don't seem a very popular character, observed the latter, and now, my good woman,

00:54:28.900 --> 00:54:32.200
just let me and this gentleman have a look about us.

00:54:33.700 --> 00:54:38.900
In the whole extent of the house, which but for the old woman remained otherwise empty,

00:54:38.900 --> 00:54:45.700
Mr. Hyde had only used a couple of rooms, but these were furnished with luxury and good taste.

00:54:46.140 --> 00:54:53.560
A closet was filled with wine, the plate was of silver, the napery elegant, a good picture

00:54:53.560 --> 00:55:00.220
hung upon the walls, a gift, as Utterson supposed, from Henry Jekyll, who was much of a connoisseur,

00:55:00.500 --> 00:55:04.420
and the carpets were of many plies and agreeable in colour.

00:55:05.120 --> 00:55:12.140
At this moment, however, the rooms bore every mark of having been recently and hurriedly ransacked.

00:55:12.480 --> 00:55:18.980
Clothes lay about the floor, with their pockets inside out, lock fast drawers stood open, and on

00:55:18.980 --> 00:55:26.060
the hearth there lay a pile of grey ashes, as though many papers had been burned. From these

00:55:26.060 --> 00:55:32.180
ambers the inspector disinterred the butt-end of a green check-book, which had resisted the action

00:55:32.180 --> 00:55:38.480
of the fire. The other half of the stick was found behind the door, and as this clenched

00:55:38.480 --> 00:55:45.780
his suspicions, the officer declared himself delighted. A visit to the bank, where several

00:55:45.780 --> 00:55:51.200
thousand pounds were found to be lying in the murderer's credit, completed his gratification.

00:55:52.200 --> 00:55:56.040
You may depend upon it, sir,' he told Mr. Utterson.

00:55:56.440 --> 00:56:02.280
I have him in my hand. He must have lost his head, or he never would have left the stick,

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:07.300
or above all burned the check-book. Why, money's life to the man.

00:56:07.740 --> 00:56:13.000
We have nothing to do but wait for him at the bank, and get out the hand-bills.'

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:21.120
This last, however, was not so easy of accomplishment, for Mr. Hyde had numbered few

00:56:21.120 --> 00:56:27.160
familiars, even the master of the servant maid had only seen him twice, his family could nowhere

00:56:27.160 --> 00:56:33.440
be traced, he had never been photographed, and the few who could describe him differed widely,

00:56:33.820 --> 00:56:41.640
as common observers will. Only on one point were they agreed, and that was the haunting sense of

00:56:41.640 --> 00:56:46.300
unexpressed deformity with which the fugitive impressed his beholder.

00:56:49.960 --> 00:56:51.680
Incident of the Letter

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:58.920
It was late in the afternoon when Mr. Utterson found his way to Dr. Jekyll's door,

00:56:59.240 --> 00:57:05.100
where he was at once admitted by Poole, and carried down by the kitchen offices and across

00:57:05.100 --> 00:57:10.340
the yard which had once been a garden, to the building that was indifferently known as the

00:57:10.340 --> 00:57:16.700
laboratory, or dissecting rooms. The doctor had bought the house from the heirs of a celebrated

00:57:16.700 --> 00:57:23.460
surgeon, and his own tastes being rather chemical than anatomical, had changed the destination of

00:57:23.460 --> 00:57:29.260
the block at the bottom of the garden. It was the first time that the lawyer had been received in

00:57:29.260 --> 00:57:35.260
that part of his friend's quarters, and he eyed the dingy, windowless structure with curiosity,

00:57:35.260 --> 00:57:40.500
and gazed round with a distasteful sense of strangeness as he crossed the theatre,

00:57:41.200 --> 00:57:48.280
once crowded with eager students, and now lying gaunt and silent, the tables laden with chemical

00:57:48.280 --> 00:57:53.800
apparatus, the floor strewn with crates and littered with packing-straw, and the light

00:57:53.800 --> 00:58:02.000
falling dimly through the foggy cupola. At the further end a flight of stairs mounted to a door

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:08.820
covered with red bays, and through this Mr. Utterson was at last received into the doctor's

00:58:08.820 --> 00:58:16.380
cabinet. It was a large room fitted round with glass presses, furnished, among other things,

00:58:16.520 --> 00:58:23.420
with a cheval glass and a business table, and looking out upon the court by three dusty windows

00:58:23.420 --> 00:58:30.540
barred with iron. The fire burned in the grate, a lamp was set lighted on the chimney shelf,

00:58:30.540 --> 00:58:38.140
for even in the houses the fog began to lie thickly, and there, close up to the warmth,

00:58:38.640 --> 00:58:45.800
sat Dr. Jekyll, looking deathly sick. He did not rise to meet his visitor,

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:50.760
but held out a cold hand and bade him welcome in a changed voice.

00:58:52.060 --> 00:58:58.340
And now, said Mr. Utterson, as soon as Poole had left them, you have heard the news?

00:58:59.260 --> 00:59:00.740
The doctor shuddered.

00:59:01.920 --> 00:59:07.480
They were crying it in the square, he said. I heard them in my dining-room.

00:59:08.600 --> 00:59:17.320
One word, said the lawyer. Karoo was my client, but so are you, and I want to know what I am doing.

00:59:18.240 --> 00:59:21.420
You have not been mad enough to hide this fellow.

00:59:22.860 --> 00:59:31.160
Utterson, I swear to God, cried the doctor, I swear to God I will never set eyes on him again.

00:59:31.880 --> 00:59:39.320
I bind my honour to you that I am done with him in this world. It is all at an end.

00:59:40.220 --> 00:59:47.880
And indeed he does not want my help. You do not know him as I do. He is safe, he is quite safe.

00:59:47.880 --> 00:59:52.200
Mark my words, he will never more be heard of.

00:59:53.420 --> 00:59:59.220
The lawyer listened gloomily. He did not like his friend's feverish manner.

00:59:59.940 --> 01:00:06.240
You seem pretty sure of him, said he, and for your sake I hope you may be right.

01:00:06.800 --> 01:00:09.840
If it came to a trial, your name might appear.

01:00:10.460 --> 01:00:17.180
I am quite sure of him, replied Jekyll. I have grounds for certainty that

01:00:17.180 --> 01:00:23.280
I cannot share with anyone. But there is one thing on which you may advise me.

01:00:23.780 --> 01:00:29.440
I have received a letter, and I am at a loss whether I should show it to the police.

01:00:30.400 --> 01:00:33.620
I should like to leave it in your hands, Utterson.

01:00:34.160 --> 01:00:39.740
You would judge wisely, I am sure. I have so great a trust in you.

01:00:40.620 --> 01:00:45.600
You fear, I suppose, that it might lead to his detection? asked the lawyer.

01:00:46.360 --> 01:00:54.000
No, said the other, I cannot say that I care what becomes of Hyde. I am quite done with him.

01:00:54.440 --> 01:01:00.040
I was thinking of my own character, which this hateful business has rather exposed.

01:01:01.420 --> 01:01:06.300
Utterson ruminated awhile. He was surprised at his friend's selfishness,

01:01:06.460 --> 01:01:08.640
and yet relieved by it.

01:01:09.460 --> 01:01:13.700
Well, said he at last, let me see the letter.

01:01:14.740 --> 01:01:21.760
The letter was written in an odd upright hand, and signed Edward Hyde, and it signified,

01:01:22.160 --> 01:01:28.580
briefly enough, that the writer's benefactor, Dr. Jekyll, whom he had long so unworthily

01:01:28.580 --> 01:01:34.520
repaid for a thousand generosities, need labour under no alarm for his safety,

01:01:35.040 --> 01:01:39.300
as he had means of escape on which he placed a sure dependence.

01:01:40.080 --> 01:01:46.700
The lawyer liked this letter well enough. It put a better colour on the intimacy than he had looked

01:01:46.700 --> 01:01:51.260
for, and he blamed himself for some of his past suspicions.

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:54.660
Have you the envelope? he asked.

01:01:55.800 --> 01:02:01.080
I burned it, replied Jekyll, before I thought what I was about.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:06.040
But it bore no postmark. The note was handed in.

01:02:06.750 --> 01:02:10.760
Shall I keep this and sleep upon it? asked Utterson.

01:02:11.740 --> 01:02:19.340
I wish you to judge for me entirely, was the reply. I have lost confidence in myself.

01:02:21.020 --> 01:02:28.200
Well, I shall consider, returned the lawyer. And now one word more.

01:02:28.700 --> 01:02:33.240
It was Hyde who dictated the terms in your will about that disappearance?

01:02:33.960 --> 01:02:41.060
The doctor seemed seized with a qualm of faintness. He shut his mouth tight and nodded.

01:02:42.120 --> 01:02:48.860
I knew it, said Utterson. He meant to murder you. You had a fine escape.

01:02:49.740 --> 01:02:54.800
I have had what is far more to the purpose, returned the doctor solemnly.

01:02:55.180 --> 01:03:01.740
I have had a lesson. O God, Utterson, what a lesson I have had!

01:03:02.340 --> 01:03:05.880
And he covered his face for a moment with his hands.

01:03:07.460 --> 01:03:11.740
On his way out, the lawyer stopped and had a word or two with Poole.

01:03:12.560 --> 01:03:19.340
By the by, said he. There was a letter handed in to-day. What was the messenger like?

01:03:20.240 --> 01:03:23.880
But Poole was positive nothing had come except by post.

01:03:24.660 --> 01:03:27.620
At only circulars by that, he added.

01:03:28.980 --> 01:03:36.200
This news sent off the visitor with his fears renewed. Plainly, the letter had come by the

01:03:36.200 --> 01:03:42.940
laboratory door. Possibly, indeed, it had been written in the cabinet. And if that were so,

01:03:43.060 --> 01:03:47.400
it must be differently judged, and handled with the more caution.

01:03:48.560 --> 01:03:53.400
The newsboys, as he went, were crying themselves hoarse along the footways.

01:03:53.960 --> 01:03:58.000
Special edition! Shocking murder of an MP!

01:03:59.400 --> 01:04:05.780
That was the funeral oration of one friend and client, and he could not help a certain

01:04:05.780 --> 01:04:11.300
apprehension lest the good name of another should be sucked down in the eddy of the scandal.

01:04:12.520 --> 01:04:19.500
It was, at last, a ticklish decision that he had to make, and self-reliant as he was by habit,

01:04:19.500 --> 01:04:25.780
he began to cherish a longing for advice. It was not to be had directly,

01:04:26.320 --> 01:04:29.940
but perhaps, he thought, it might be fished for.

01:04:31.660 --> 01:04:37.960
Presently after, he sat on one side of his own hearth, with Mr. Guest, his head clerk,

01:04:37.980 --> 01:04:43.420
upon the other, and midway between, at a nicely calculated distance from the fire,

01:04:43.420 --> 01:04:50.520
a bottle of a particular old wine that had long dwelt unsund in the foundation of his house.

01:04:51.660 --> 01:04:58.460
The fog still slept on the wing above the drowned city, where the lamps glimmered like carbuncles,

01:04:58.840 --> 01:05:05.040
and through the muffle and smother of these fallen clouds, the procession of the town's life was

01:05:05.040 --> 01:05:12.620
still rolling in through the great arteries with a sound as of a mighty wind. But the room was

01:05:12.620 --> 01:05:19.760
with firelight. In the bottle, the acids were long ago resolved, the imperial dye had softened with

01:05:19.760 --> 01:05:26.260
time, as the colour grows richer in stained windows, and the glow of hot autumn afternoons

01:05:26.260 --> 01:05:31.740
on hillside vineyards was ready to be set free and disperse the fogs of London.

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:40.480
Insensibly, the lawyer melted. There was no man from whom he kept fewer secrets than Mr. Guest,

01:05:40.480 --> 01:05:47.140
and he was not always sure that he kept as many as he meant. Guest had often been on business to

01:05:47.140 --> 01:05:53.400
the doctors, a new pool, he could scarce have failed to hear of Mr. Hyde's familiarity about

01:05:53.400 --> 01:06:00.920
the house. He might draw conclusions. Was it not as well, then, that he should see a letter which

01:06:00.920 --> 01:06:07.370
put that mystery to right? And above all, since Guest, being a great student and critic of

01:06:07.370 --> 01:06:14.270
would consider the step natural and obliging. The clerk, besides, was a man of counsel.

01:06:14.810 --> 01:06:21.670
He could scarce read so strange a document without dropping a remark, and by that remark

01:06:21.670 --> 01:06:29.490
Mr. Utterson might shape his future course. This is a sad business about Sir Danvers, he said.

01:06:30.230 --> 01:06:35.270
Yes, sir, indeed. It has elicited a great deal of public feeling,

01:06:35.750 --> 01:06:39.110
returned Guest. The man, of course, was mad.

01:06:39.970 --> 01:06:46.510
I should like to hear your views on that, replied Utterson. I have a document here in his

01:06:46.510 --> 01:06:53.850
handwriting. It is between ourselves, for I scarce know what to do about it. It is an ugly

01:06:53.850 --> 01:07:00.810
business at the best, but there it is, quite in your way, a murderer's autograph.

01:07:02.550 --> 01:07:07.150
Guest's eyes brightened, and he sat down at once and studied it with passion.

01:07:08.370 --> 01:07:17.390
No, sir, he said, not mad, but it is an odd hand. And by all accounts a very odd writer,

01:07:17.390 --> 01:07:21.890
added the lawyer. Just then the servant entered with a note.

01:07:22.930 --> 01:07:29.030
Is that from Dr. Jekyll, sir? inquired the clerk. I thought I knew the writing.

01:07:30.210 --> 01:07:32.370
Anything private, Mr. Utterson?

01:07:33.690 --> 01:07:38.570
Only an invitation to dinner. Why? Do you want to see it?

01:07:39.310 --> 01:07:45.470
One moment, I thank you, sir. And the clerk laid the two sheets of paper alongside,

01:07:45.470 --> 01:07:48.110
and sedulously compared their contents.

01:07:49.470 --> 01:07:56.850
Thank you, sir, he said at last, returning both. It's a very interesting autograph.

01:07:58.150 --> 01:08:02.530
There was a pause, during which Mr. Utterson struggled with himself.

01:08:03.770 --> 01:08:07.850
Why did you compare them, Guest? he inquired suddenly.

01:08:08.800 --> 01:08:14.030
Well, sir, returned the clerk, there's a rather singular resemblance.

01:08:14.550 --> 01:08:18.920
The two hands are in many points identical, only differently sloped.

01:08:21.130 --> 01:08:28.230
Rather quaint, said Utterson. It is, as you say, rather quaint, returned Guest.

01:08:29.550 --> 01:08:33.950
I wouldn't speak of this note, you know, said the master.

01:08:34.810 --> 01:08:39.090
No, sir, said the clerk. I understand.

01:08:42.010 --> 01:08:45.930
But no sooner was Mr. Utterson alone that night,

01:08:46.070 --> 01:08:51.250
than he locked the note into his safe, where it reposed from that time forward.

01:08:52.530 --> 01:09:01.130
What? he thought. Henry Jekyll forged for a murderer, and his blood ran cold in his veins.

01:09:06.010 --> 01:09:07.890
Incident of Dr. Lanyon

01:09:09.830 --> 01:09:16.410
Time ran on. Thousands of pounds were offered in reward, for the death of Sir Danvers was

01:09:16.410 --> 01:09:22.950
resented as a public injury. But Mr. Hyde had disappeared out of the ken of the police,

01:09:23.090 --> 01:09:29.710
as though he had never existed. Much of his past was unearthed, indeed, and all disreputable.

01:09:29.710 --> 01:09:36.450
Tales came out of the man's cruelty, at once so callous and violent, of his vile life,

01:09:36.530 --> 01:09:41.870
of his strange associates, of the hatred that seemed to have surrounded his career,

01:09:42.590 --> 01:09:49.630
but of his present whereabouts not a whisper. From the time he had left his house in Soho,

01:09:49.770 --> 01:09:56.470
on the morning of the murder, he was simply blotted out, and gradually, as time drew on,

01:09:56.470 --> 01:10:03.210
Mr. Utterson began to recover from the hotness of his alarm, and to grow more at quiet with

01:10:03.210 --> 01:10:10.590
himself. The death of Sir Danvers was, to his way of thinking, more than paid for by the

01:10:10.590 --> 01:10:18.010
disappearance of Mr. Hyde. Now that that evil influence had been withdrawn, a new life began

01:10:18.010 --> 01:10:25.270
for Dr. Jekyll. He came out of his seclusion, renewed relations with his friends, became once

01:10:25.270 --> 01:10:30.950
their familiar guest and entertainer, and whilst he had always been known for charities,

01:10:31.410 --> 01:10:38.810
he was now no less distinguished for religion. He was busy, he was much in the open air,

01:10:39.150 --> 01:10:46.250
he did good, his face seemed to open and brighten, as if with an inward consciousness of service,

01:10:46.670 --> 01:10:51.150
and for more than two months the doctor was at peace.

01:10:52.790 --> 01:10:59.710
On the eighth of January Utterson had dined at the doctor's with a small party. Lanyon had been

01:10:59.710 --> 01:11:05.150
there, and the face of the host had looked from one to the other as in the old days,

01:11:05.170 --> 01:11:11.150
when the trio were inseparable friends. On the twelfth and again on the fourteenth,

01:11:11.670 --> 01:11:13.950
the door was shut against the lawyer.

01:11:14.830 --> 01:11:20.970
The doctor was confined to the house, Poole said, and saw no one.

01:11:22.270 --> 01:11:28.710
On the fifteenth he tried again, and was again refused, and having now been used for the last

01:11:28.710 --> 01:11:34.990
two months to see his friend almost daily, he found this return of solitude to weigh upon

01:11:34.990 --> 01:11:42.430
his spirits. The fifth night he had ingest to dine with him, and the sixth he betook himself

01:11:42.430 --> 01:11:51.150
to Dr. Lanyon. There at least he was not denied admittance, but when he came in he was shocked

01:11:51.150 --> 01:11:56.910
at the change which had taken place in the doctor's appearance. He had his death warrant

01:11:56.910 --> 01:12:03.610
written legibly upon his face. The rosy man had grown pale, his flesh had fallen away,

01:12:04.010 --> 01:12:11.330
he was visibly bolder and older, and yet it was not so much these tokens of a swift physical

01:12:11.330 --> 01:12:17.850
decay that arrested the lawyer's notice, as a look in the eye and quality of manner that

01:12:17.850 --> 01:12:25.010
seemed to testify to some deep-seated terror of the mind. It was unlikely that the doctor

01:12:25.010 --> 01:12:30.010
should fear death, and yet that was what Utterson was tempted to suspect.

01:12:31.270 --> 01:12:39.530
Yes, he thought, he is a doctor, he must know his own state, and that his days are counted,

01:12:40.050 --> 01:12:47.230
and the knowledge is more than he can bear. And yet, when Utterson remarked on his ill looks,

01:12:47.810 --> 01:12:53.670
it was with an air of great firmness that Lanyon declared himself a doomed man.

01:12:55.370 --> 01:13:02.590
I have had a shock, he said, and I shall never recover. It is a question of weeks.

01:13:03.650 --> 01:13:10.030
Well, life has been pleasant. I liked it. Yes, sir, I used to like it.

01:13:10.310 --> 01:13:14.290
I sometimes think if we knew all, we should be more glad to get away.

01:13:15.930 --> 01:13:19.670
Jekyll is ill too, observed Utterson. Have you seen him?

01:13:21.010 --> 01:13:25.070
But Lanyon's face changed, and he held up a trembling hand.

01:13:25.070 --> 01:13:31.590
I wish to see or hear no more of Dr. Jekyll, he said in a loud,

01:13:32.050 --> 01:13:35.550
unsteady voice. I am quite done with that person,

01:13:35.910 --> 01:13:41.830
and I beg that you will spare me any allusion to one whom I regard as dead.

01:13:43.010 --> 01:13:48.690
Tut, tut, said Mr. Utterson, and then, after a considerable pause,

01:13:49.330 --> 01:13:55.590
Can't I do anything? he inquired. We are three very old friends, Lanyon.

01:13:56.070 --> 01:13:58.290
We shall not live to make others.

01:13:59.250 --> 01:14:03.470
Nothing can be done, returned Lanyon. Ask himself.

01:14:04.410 --> 01:14:06.910
He will not see me, said the lawyer.

01:14:07.870 --> 01:14:15.430
I am not surprised at that, was the reply. Someday, Utterson, after I am dead,

01:14:15.430 --> 01:14:21.510
you may perhaps come to learn the right and wrong of this. I cannot tell you.

01:14:21.950 --> 01:14:25.990
And in the meantime, if you can sit and talk with me of other things,

01:14:26.210 --> 01:14:32.230
for God's sake stay and do so. But if you cannot keep clear of this accursed topic,

01:14:32.730 --> 01:14:36.950
then in God's name go, for I cannot bear it.

01:14:38.470 --> 01:14:44.530
As soon as he got home, Utterson sat down and wrote to Jekyll, complaining of his exclusion

01:14:44.530 --> 01:14:48.790
from the house, and asking the cause of this unhappy break with Lanyon.

01:14:49.470 --> 01:14:54.670
And the next day brought him a long answer, often very pathetically worded,

01:14:54.830 --> 01:15:01.510
and sometimes darkly mysterious in drift. The quarrel with Lanyon was incurable.

01:15:01.930 --> 01:15:09.690
I do not blame our old friend, Jekyll wrote, but I share his view that we must never meet.

01:15:10.250 --> 01:15:14.670
I mean from henceforth to lead a life of extreme seclusion.

01:15:15.430 --> 01:15:19.610
You must not be surprised, nor must you doubt my friendship,

01:15:20.050 --> 01:15:27.570
if my door is often shut, even to you. You must suffer me to go my own dark way.

01:15:28.170 --> 01:15:33.850
I have brought on myself a punishment and a danger that I cannot name.

01:15:34.790 --> 01:15:40.810
If I am the chief of sinners, I am the chief of sufferers also.

01:15:41.670 --> 01:15:48.450
I could not think that this earth contained a place for sufferings and terrors so unmanning.

01:15:48.970 --> 01:15:57.530
And you can do but one thing, Utterson, to lighten this destiny, and that is to respect my silence.

01:15:58.970 --> 01:16:03.670
Utterson was amazed. The dark influence of Hyde had been withdrawn.

01:16:04.130 --> 01:16:10.770
The doctor had returned to his old tasks and amities. A week ago the prospect had smiled with

01:16:10.770 --> 01:16:18.470
every promise of a cheerful and an honoured age, and now, in a moment, friendship and peace of mind

01:16:18.470 --> 01:16:25.970
and the whole tenor of his life were wrecked. So great and unprepared a change pointed to madness,

01:16:25.970 --> 01:16:32.590
but in view of Lanyon's words and manner, there must lie for it some deeper ground.

01:16:34.230 --> 01:16:41.750
A week afterwards Dr. Lanyon took to his bed, and in something less than a fortnight he was dead.

01:16:42.450 --> 01:16:49.570
The night after the funeral, at which he had been sadly affected, Utterson locked the door of his

01:16:49.570 --> 01:16:55.950
business room, and sitting there by the light of a melancholy candle, drew out and set before him

01:16:55.950 --> 01:17:01.730
an envelope, addressed by the hand, and sealed with the seal of his dear friend.

01:17:02.790 --> 01:17:10.790
Private for the hands of J.G. Utterson alone, and in the case of his predecease to be destroyed

01:17:10.790 --> 01:17:18.510
unread. So it was emphatically superscribed, and the lawyer dreaded to behold the contents.

01:17:19.350 --> 01:17:26.230
I have buried one friend today, he thought. What if this should cost me another?

01:17:27.170 --> 01:17:34.770
And then he condemned the fear as a disloyalty, and broke the seal. Within there was another

01:17:34.770 --> 01:17:41.810
enclosure, likewise sealed, and marked upon the cover as not to be opened till the death or

01:17:41.810 --> 01:17:43.930
disappearance of Dr. Henry Jekyll.

01:17:45.110 --> 01:17:52.270
Utterson could not trust his eyes. Yes, it was disappearance. Here again,

01:17:52.430 --> 01:17:58.810
as in the mad will which he had long ago restored to its author, here again were the idea of a

01:17:58.810 --> 01:18:05.530
disappearance in the name of Henry Jekyll bracketed. But in the will, that idea had sprung from the

01:18:06.090 --> 01:18:12.430
suggestion of the man Hyde. It was set there with a purpose all too plain and horrible.

01:18:13.210 --> 01:18:20.250
Written by the hand of Lanyon, what should it mean? A great curiosity came on the trustee

01:18:20.250 --> 01:18:25.670
to disregard the prohibition, and dive at once to the bottom of these mysteries.

01:18:26.390 --> 01:18:33.310
The professional honor and faith of his dead friend were stringent obligations, and the packet

01:18:33.310 --> 01:18:41.170
slept in the inmost corner of his private safe. It is one thing to mortify curiosity,

01:18:41.970 --> 01:18:48.730
another to conquer it. And it may be doubted if, from that day forth, Utterson desired the

01:18:48.730 --> 01:18:53.850
society of his surviving friend with the same eagerness. He thought of him kindly,

01:18:54.330 --> 01:19:01.870
but his thoughts were disquieted and fearful. He went to call indeed, but he was perhaps relieved

01:19:01.870 --> 01:19:08.050
to be denied admittance. Perhaps, in his heart, he preferred to speak with Poole about the doorstep,

01:19:08.450 --> 01:19:13.770
and surrounded by the air and sounds of the open city, rather than to be admitted into the

01:19:13.770 --> 01:19:19.530
house of voluntary bondage, and to sit and speak with its inscrutable recluse.

01:19:20.570 --> 01:19:26.670
Poole had indeed no very pleasant news to communicate. The doctor, it appeared,

01:19:26.670 --> 01:19:31.670
now more than ever, confined himself to the cabinet over the laboratory,

01:19:32.130 --> 01:19:37.930
where he would sometimes even sleep. He was out of spirits, he had grown very silent,

01:19:38.270 --> 01:19:45.910
he did not read. It seemed as if he had something on his mind. Utterson became so used to the

01:19:45.910 --> 01:19:52.530
unvarying character of these reports, that he fell off little by little in the frequency of his visit.

01:19:56.410 --> 01:19:58.310
Incidents at the Window

01:19:59.450 --> 01:20:04.970
It chanced on Sunday, when Mr. Utterson was on his usual walk with Mr. Enfield,

01:20:05.490 --> 01:20:10.830
that their way lay once again through the by-street, and that when they came in front of

01:20:10.830 --> 01:20:13.710
the door both stopped to gaze on it.

01:20:15.090 --> 01:20:22.370
"'Well,' said Enfield, "'that story's an end at least. We shall never see more of Mr. Hyde.'

01:20:22.370 --> 01:20:24.770
"'I hope not,' said Utterson.

01:20:25.350 --> 01:20:29.550
"'Did I ever tell you that I once saw him and shared your feeling of repulsion?'

01:20:30.170 --> 01:20:34.690
"'It was impossible to do one without the other,' returned Enfield.

01:20:35.070 --> 01:20:40.930
"'And by the way, what an ass you must have thought of me not to know that this was a back

01:20:40.930 --> 01:20:47.060
way to Dr. Jekyll's. It was partly your own fault that I found it out, even when I did.'

01:20:47.930 --> 01:20:51.550
"'So you found it out, did you?' said Utterson.

01:20:52.010 --> 01:20:56.850
"'But if that be so, we may step into the court and take a look at the windows.

01:20:57.310 --> 01:21:01.330
"'To tell you the truth, I am uneasy about poor Jekyll,

01:21:01.850 --> 01:21:06.900
and even outside I feel as if the presence of a friend might do him good.'

01:21:07.920 --> 01:21:14.960
"'The court was very cool and a little damp, and full of premature twilight, although the sky,

01:21:15.260 --> 01:21:22.260
high up overhead, was still bright with sunset. The middle of one of the three windows was halfway

01:21:22.260 --> 01:21:28.280
open, and sitting close beside it, taking the air with an infinite sadness of mean,

01:21:28.700 --> 01:21:33.240
like some disconsolate prisoner, Utterson saw Dr. Jekyll.

01:21:34.000 --> 01:21:38.320
"'What, Jekyll?' he cried. "'I trust you are better?'

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:44.040
"'I am very low, Utterson,' replied the doctor drearily.

01:21:44.580 --> 01:21:49.300
"'Very low. It will not last long, thank God.'

01:21:50.540 --> 01:21:53.900
"'You stay too much indoors,' said the lawyer.

01:21:54.060 --> 01:21:58.700
"'You should be out whipping up the circulation like Mr. Enfield and me.

01:21:59.340 --> 01:22:03.000
This is my cousin, Mr. Enfield, Dr. Jekyll.

01:22:03.700 --> 01:22:07.620
Come now, get your hat, and take a quick turn with us.'

01:22:08.500 --> 01:22:11.520
"'You are very good,' sighed the other.

01:22:11.700 --> 01:22:20.640
"'I should like to very much. But no, no, no, it is quite impossible. I dare not.'

01:22:21.980 --> 01:22:27.920
"'But indeed, Utterson, I am very glad to see you. This is really a great pleasure.'

01:22:28.700 --> 01:22:34.160
"'I would ask you and Mr. Enfield up, but the place is really not fit.'

01:22:34.960 --> 01:22:37.900
"'Why then?' said the lawyer good-naturedly.

01:22:37.900 --> 01:22:42.440
"'The best thing we can do is to stay down here and speak with you from where we are.'

01:22:43.220 --> 01:22:49.840
"'That is just what I was about to venture to propose,' returned the doctor with a smile.

01:22:50.680 --> 01:22:55.960
But the words were hardly uttered before the smile was struck out of his face,

01:22:55.960 --> 01:23:00.260
and succeeded by an expression of such abject terror and despair

01:23:00.260 --> 01:23:04.260
as froze the very blood of the two gentlemen below.

01:23:05.260 --> 01:23:10.200
They saw it but for a glimpse, for the window was instantly thrust down,

01:23:10.900 --> 01:23:17.040
but that glimpse had been sufficient, and they turned and left the court without a word.

01:23:18.380 --> 01:23:24.440
In silence too they traversed the by-street, and it was not until they had come into a

01:23:24.440 --> 01:23:30.100
thoroughfare, where even upon a Sunday there were still some stirrings of life,

01:23:30.680 --> 01:23:34.800
that Mr. Utterson at last turned and looked at his companion.

01:23:35.900 --> 01:23:40.600
They were both pale, and there was an answering horror in their eyes.

01:23:41.840 --> 01:23:48.180
"'God forgive us! God forgive us!' said Mr. Utterson.

01:23:48.180 --> 01:23:56.980
But Mr. Enfield only nodded his head very seriously, and walked on once more in silence.

01:24:31.201 --> 01:24:35.801
THE LAST NIGHT

01:24:36.781 --> 01:24:42.141
Mr. Utterson was sitting by his friends one evening after dinner, when he was surprised

01:24:42.141 --> 01:24:44.341
to receive a visit from Poole.

01:24:44.881 --> 01:24:50.601
"'Bless me, Poole, what brings you here?' he cried, and then taking a second look at

01:24:50.601 --> 01:24:50.961
him.

01:24:51.341 --> 01:24:53.321
"'What ails you?' he added.

01:24:53.321 --> 01:24:55.641
"'Is the doctor ill?'

01:24:55.641 --> 01:25:00.941
"'Mr. Utterson,' said the man, "'there is something wrong.'

01:25:00.941 --> 01:25:05.521
"'Take a seat, and here is a glass of wine for you,' said the lawyer.

01:25:06.521 --> 01:25:10.341
"'Now take your time, and tell me plainly what you want.'

01:25:12.181 --> 01:25:18.481
"'You know the doctor's ways, sir,' replied Poole, and how he shuts himself up.

01:25:18.821 --> 01:25:25.641
"'While he's shot up again in the cabinet, and I don't like it, sir, I wish I may die

01:25:25.641 --> 01:25:27.101
if I like it.

01:25:27.481 --> 01:25:30.161
Mr. Utterson, sir, I am afraid.'

01:25:31.241 --> 01:25:35.401
"'Now, my good man,' said the lawyer, "'be explicit.

01:25:35.881 --> 01:25:37.881
What are you afraid of?'

01:25:38.981 --> 01:25:45.241
"'I've been afraid for about a week,' returned Poole, doggedly disregarding the question,

01:25:45.581 --> 01:25:49.041
"'and I can bear it no more.'

01:25:49.321 --> 01:25:52.201
The man's appearance amply bore out his words.

01:25:52.741 --> 01:25:57.661
His manner was altered for the worse, and except for the moment when he had first announced

01:25:57.661 --> 01:26:01.501
his terror, he had not once looked the lawyer in the face.

01:26:02.281 --> 01:26:08.721
Even now he sat with the glass of wine untasted on his knee, and his eyes directed to a corner

01:26:08.721 --> 01:26:09.461
of the floor.

01:26:10.361 --> 01:26:14.281
"'I can bear it no more,' he repeated.

01:26:15.361 --> 01:26:19.481
"'Come,' said the lawyer, "'I see you have some good reason, Poole.

01:26:19.561 --> 01:26:22.321
I see there is something seriously amiss.

01:26:22.901 --> 01:26:26.261
Try to tell me what it is.'

01:26:26.261 --> 01:26:31.901
"'I think there's been foul play,' said Poole, hoarsely.

01:26:33.261 --> 01:26:34.661
"'Foul play?'

01:26:34.661 --> 01:26:35.681
cried the lawyer.

01:26:36.121 --> 01:26:40.941
"'A good deal frightened, and rather inclined to be irritated in consequence.

01:26:41.161 --> 01:26:42.401
What foul play?

01:26:42.641 --> 01:26:45.461
What does this man mean?'

01:26:45.461 --> 01:26:49.021
"'I dare not say, sir,' was the answer.

01:26:49.401 --> 01:26:53.641
"'But will you come along with me and see for yourself?'

01:26:53.641 --> 01:27:00.521
Mr. Utterson's only answer was to rise and get his hat and greatcoat, but he observed

01:27:00.521 --> 01:27:06.121
with wonder the greatness of the relief that appeared upon the butler's face, and perhaps

01:27:06.121 --> 01:27:11.061
with no less that the wine was still untasted when he set it down to follow.

01:27:13.061 --> 01:27:19.561
It was a wild, cold, seasonable night of March, with a pale moon lying on her back as though

01:27:19.561 --> 01:27:25.161
the wind had tilted her, and flying rack of the most diaphanous and lawny texture.

01:27:26.221 --> 01:27:30.581
The wind made talking difficult, and flecked the blood into the face.

01:27:31.261 --> 01:27:37.681
It seemed to have swept the streets unusually bare of passengers, besides, for Mr. Utterson

01:27:37.681 --> 01:27:40.801
thought he had never seen that part of London so deserted.

01:27:41.481 --> 01:27:46.521
He could have wished it otherwise, never in his life had he been conscious of so sharp

01:27:46.521 --> 01:27:52.781
wish to see and touch his fellow creatures, for struggle as he might, there was borne

01:27:52.781 --> 01:27:56.701
in upon his mind a crushing anticipation of calamity.

01:27:57.481 --> 01:28:02.781
The square, when they got there, was full of wind and dust, and the thin trees in the

01:28:02.781 --> 01:28:05.221
garden were lashing themselves along the railing.

01:28:05.821 --> 01:28:11.241
Poole, who had kept all the way a pace or two ahead, now pulled up in the middle of

01:28:11.241 --> 01:28:17.101
the pavement, and in spite of the biting weather, took off his hat and mopped his brow with

01:28:17.101 --> 01:28:18.561
a red pocket handkerchief.

01:28:19.441 --> 01:28:24.861
But for all the hurry of his coming, these were not the dews of exertion that he wiped

01:28:24.861 --> 01:28:32.041
away, but the moisture of some strangling anguish, for his face was white, and his voice

01:28:32.041 --> 01:28:34.621
when he spoke harsh and broken.

01:28:35.481 --> 01:28:42.351
"'Well, sir,' he said, "'here we are, and God grant there be nothing wrong.'

01:28:43.621 --> 01:28:46.161
"'Amen, Poole,' said the lawyer.

01:28:47.401 --> 01:28:50.641
Thereupon the servant knocked in a very guarded manner.

01:28:51.241 --> 01:28:58.261
The door was opened on the chain, and a voice asked from within, "'Is that you, Poole?'

01:28:58.261 --> 01:29:03.121
"'It's all right,' said Poole, "'open the door.'"

01:29:03.121 --> 01:29:09.361
The hall, when they entered it, was brightly lighted up, the fire was built high, and about

01:29:09.361 --> 01:29:14.601
the hearth the whole of the servants, men and women, stood huddled together like a flock

01:29:14.601 --> 01:29:15.241
of sheep.

01:29:16.441 --> 01:29:22.221
At the sight of Mr. Utterson, the housemaid broke into hysterical whimpering, and the

01:29:22.221 --> 01:29:29.601
cook, crying out, "'Bless God, it's Mr. Utterson!' ran forward as if to take him in her arms.

01:29:30.541 --> 01:29:36.561
"'What, what, are you all here?' said the lawyer, peevishly.

01:29:36.681 --> 01:29:39.221
"'Very irregular, very unseemly.

01:29:39.421 --> 01:29:41.761
Your master would be far from pleased.'

01:29:42.801 --> 01:29:45.761
"'They're all afraid,' said Poole.

01:29:46.881 --> 01:29:50.321
Black silence followed, no one protesting.

01:29:50.801 --> 01:29:54.421
Only the maid lifted her voice, and now wept loudly.

01:29:55.141 --> 01:30:01.341
"'Hold your tongue,' Poole said to her, with a ferocity of accent that testified to his

01:30:01.341 --> 01:30:07.841
own jangled nerves, and indeed, when the girl had so suddenly raised the note of her lamentation,

01:30:08.141 --> 01:30:13.661
they had all started and turned towards the inner door with faces of dreadful expectation.

01:30:15.561 --> 01:30:22.401
"'And now,' continued the butler, addressing the knife-boy, "'reach me a candle, and we'll

01:30:22.401 --> 01:30:25.501
get this through hands at once.'

01:30:25.501 --> 01:30:31.041
And then he begged Mr. Utterson to follow him, and led the way to the back garden.

01:30:32.781 --> 01:30:37.521
"'Now, sir,' said he, "'you come as gently as you can.

01:30:37.941 --> 01:30:41.721
I want you to hear, and I don't want you to be heard.

01:30:42.281 --> 01:30:49.561
And see here, sir, if by any chance he was to ask you in, don't go.'

01:30:49.561 --> 01:30:56.041
Mr. Utterson's nerves, at this unlooked-for termination, gave a jerk that nearly threw

01:30:56.041 --> 01:31:02.021
him from his balance, but he recollected his courage and followed the butler into the laboratory

01:31:02.021 --> 01:31:07.421
building through the surgical theatre, with its lumber of crates and bottles, to the foot

01:31:07.421 --> 01:31:08.261
of the stair.

01:31:09.341 --> 01:31:15.961
Here, Poole motioned him to stand on one side and listen, while he himself, setting down

01:31:15.961 --> 01:31:21.341
the candle and making a great and obvious call on his resolution, mounted the steps

01:31:21.341 --> 01:31:26.341
and knocked with a somewhat uncertain hand on the red bays of the cabinet door.

01:31:27.661 --> 01:31:35.721
"'Mr. Utterson, sir, asking to see you,' he called, and even as he did so, once more

01:31:35.721 --> 01:31:38.701
violently signed to the lawyer to give ear.

01:31:39.641 --> 01:31:42.261
A voice answered from within,

01:31:43.481 --> 01:31:48.661
"'Tell him I cannot see any one,' it said complainingly.

01:31:49.181 --> 01:31:56.221
"'Thank you, sir,' said Poole, with a note of something like triumph in his voice, and

01:31:56.221 --> 01:32:01.901
taking up his candle, he led Mr. Utterson back across the yard and into the great kitchen,

01:32:02.421 --> 01:32:06.361
where the fire was out and the beetles were leaping on the floor.

01:32:07.381 --> 01:32:10.801
"'Sir,' he said, looking Mr. Utterson in the eyes,

01:32:10.841 --> 01:32:13.861
"'was that my master's voice?'

01:32:15.021 --> 01:32:21.021
"'It seems much changed,' replied the lawyer, very pale, but giving look for look.

01:32:22.201 --> 01:32:26.641
"'Changed? Well, yes, I think so,' said the butler.

01:32:26.981 --> 01:32:32.141
"'Have I been twenty years in this man's house to be deceived about his voice?

01:32:32.781 --> 01:32:39.581
"'No, sir. Master's made away with. He was made away with eight days ago when we heard him cry

01:32:39.581 --> 01:32:46.281
out upon the name of God, and who's in there instead of him, and why it stays there is a

01:32:46.281 --> 01:32:49.541
thing that cries to heaven, Mr. Utterson.'

01:32:49.541 --> 01:32:57.041
"'This is a very strange tale, Poole. This is rather a wild tale, my man,' said Mr. Utterson,

01:32:57.401 --> 01:32:58.601
biting his finger.

01:32:58.601 --> 01:33:03.801
"'Suppose it were as you suppose, supposing Dr. Jekyll to have been,

01:33:04.301 --> 01:33:10.581
well, murdered. What could induce the murderer to stay? That won't hold water.

01:33:10.881 --> 01:33:13.101
It doesn't commend itself to reason.'

01:33:13.921 --> 01:33:18.041
"'Well, Mr. Utterson, you are a hard man to satisfy.'

01:33:18.721 --> 01:33:21.381
"'But I'll do it yet,' said Poole.

01:33:21.381 --> 01:33:29.561
"'All this last week, you must know, him, or it, or whatever it is that lives in that cabinet,

01:33:30.001 --> 01:33:36.021
has been crying night and day for some sort of medicine, and cannot get it to his mind.

01:33:36.661 --> 01:33:43.041
It was sometimes his way, the Master's, that is, to write his orders on a sheet of paper

01:33:43.041 --> 01:33:49.881
and throw it on the stair. We've had nothing else this week back, nothing but papers and a

01:33:49.881 --> 01:33:54.881
door, and the very meals left there to be smuggled in when nobody was looking.

01:33:55.781 --> 01:34:03.281
Well, sir, every day—I and twice and thrice in the same day—there have been orders and

01:34:03.281 --> 01:34:08.401
complaints, and I have been sent flying to all the wholesale chemists in town.

01:34:09.161 --> 01:34:14.641
Every time I brought the stuff back there would be another paper telling me to return it,

01:34:14.741 --> 01:34:19.341
because it was not pure, and another order to a different firm.

01:34:19.881 --> 01:34:24.401
This drug is wanted bitter bad, sir, whatever for.'

01:34:25.721 --> 01:34:29.741
"'Have you any of these papers?' asked Mr. Utterson.

01:34:30.181 --> 01:34:34.541
Poole felt in his pocket and handed out a crumpled note, which the lawyer,

01:34:34.941 --> 01:34:41.061
bending nearer to the candle, carefully examined. Its contents ran thus.

01:34:41.961 --> 01:34:47.921
"'Dr. Jekyll presents his compliments to Messer's maw. He assures them that their last sample is

01:34:47.921 --> 01:34:54.981
pure and quite useless for his present purpose. In the last year Dr. J. purchased a somewhat large

01:34:54.981 --> 01:35:01.641
quantity from Messer's M. He now begs them to search with most sedulous care, and should any

01:35:01.641 --> 01:35:07.841
of the same quality be left, forward it to him at once. Expense is no consideration.

01:35:08.501 --> 01:35:12.721
The importance of this to Dr. J. could hardly be exaggerated.'

01:35:12.721 --> 01:35:20.081
And so far the letter had run composedly enough, but here, with a sudden splutter of the pen,

01:35:20.741 --> 01:35:23.181
the writer's emotion had broken loose.

01:35:23.941 --> 01:35:28.201
"'For God's sake,' he added, "'find me some of the old.'

01:35:28.901 --> 01:35:33.541
"'This is a strange note,' said Utterson, and then sharply,

01:35:33.781 --> 01:35:35.921
"'How do you come to have it open?'

01:35:36.741 --> 01:35:43.821
"'The man at Maw's was main angry, sir, and he threw it back to me like so much dirt,'

01:35:43.821 --> 01:35:44.961
returned Poole.

01:35:45.601 --> 01:35:50.801
"'This is unquestionably the doctor's hand, do you know?' resumed the lawyer.

01:35:51.801 --> 01:35:57.841
"'I thought it looked like it,' said the servant rather sulkily, and then with another voice,

01:35:57.841 --> 01:36:01.521
"'But what matters hand of right?' he said.

01:36:01.821 --> 01:36:03.231
"'I've seen him.'

01:36:04.241 --> 01:36:07.261
"'Seen him?' repeated Mr. Utterson.

01:36:08.281 --> 01:36:08.981
"'Well?'

01:36:08.981 --> 01:36:11.161
"'That's it,' said Poole.

01:36:11.161 --> 01:36:12.771
"'It was this way.'

01:36:13.701 --> 01:36:16.561
"'I came suddenly into the theatre from the garden.

01:36:17.021 --> 01:36:23.681
It seems he had slipped out to look for this drug, or whatever it is, for the cabinet door was open,

01:36:23.681 --> 01:36:28.101
and there he was at the far end of the room, digging among the crates.

01:36:28.521 --> 01:36:34.441
He looked up when I came in, gave a kind of cry, and whipped upstairs into the cabinet.

01:36:35.161 --> 01:36:42.181
It was but for one minute that I saw him, but the hair stood upon my head like quills.

01:36:43.301 --> 01:36:49.101
"'Sir, if that was my master, why had he a mask upon his face?

01:36:49.101 --> 01:36:54.521
If it was my master, why did he cry out like a rat and run from me?

01:36:55.021 --> 01:36:58.121
I have served him long enough, and then—'

01:36:59.481 --> 01:37:02.741
The man paused and passed his hand over his face.

01:37:03.541 --> 01:37:08.781
"'These are all very strange circumstances,' said Mr. Utterson,

01:37:09.181 --> 01:37:11.981
"'but I think I begin to see daylight.

01:37:11.981 --> 01:37:18.681
Your master, Poole, is plainly seized with one of those maladies that both torture and

01:37:18.681 --> 01:37:26.061
deform the sufferer. Hence, for aught I know, the alteration of his voice, hence the mask and the

01:37:26.061 --> 01:37:32.161
avoidance of his friends, hence the eagerness to find this drug, by means of which the poor

01:37:32.161 --> 01:37:37.981
soul retains some hope of ultimate recovery. God grant that he be not deceived.

01:37:38.701 --> 01:37:44.641
There is my explanation. It is sad enough, Poole, I, and appalling to consider,

01:37:45.301 --> 01:37:52.141
but it is plain and natural, hangs well together, and delivers us from all exorbitant alarms.'

01:37:54.441 --> 01:37:58.781
"'Sir,' said the butler, turning to a sort of mottled pallor,

01:37:59.581 --> 01:38:04.351
"'that thing was not my master, and there's the truth.'

01:38:05.681 --> 01:38:09.701
"'My master,' here he looked round him and began to whisper,

01:38:10.061 --> 01:38:15.111
"'is a tall fine build of a man, and this was more of a dwarf.'

01:38:16.361 --> 01:38:18.561
Utterson attempted to protest.

01:38:19.081 --> 01:38:21.621
"'Oh, sir,' cried Poole,

01:38:21.621 --> 01:38:26.001
"'do you think I do not know my master after twenty years?

01:38:26.361 --> 01:38:30.761
Do you think I do not know where his head comes to in the cabinet door,

01:38:31.101 --> 01:38:33.381
where I saw him every morning of my life?'

01:38:34.161 --> 01:38:41.541
"'Oh, sir, that thing in the mask was never Dr. Jekyll. God knows what it is,

01:38:41.761 --> 01:38:49.301
but it was never Dr. Jekyll, and it is the belief of my heart that there was murder done.'

01:38:51.121 --> 01:38:52.901
"'Poole,' replied the lawyer,

01:38:52.941 --> 01:38:57.021
"'if you say that, it will become my duty to make certain.

01:38:57.721 --> 01:39:00.601
Much as I desire to spare your master's feelings,

01:39:01.021 --> 01:39:05.701
much as I am puzzled by this note which seems to prove him to be still alive,

01:39:06.241 --> 01:39:10.381
I still consider it my duty to break in that door.'

01:39:11.721 --> 01:39:16.681
"'Ah, Mr. Utterson, that's talking,' cried the butler.

01:39:17.721 --> 01:39:21.661
"'And now comes the second question,' resumed Utterson.

01:39:21.981 --> 01:39:23.701
"'Who is going to do it?'

01:39:24.101 --> 01:39:28.041
"'Why, you and me, sir,' was the undaunted reply.'

01:39:29.141 --> 01:39:32.161
"'That's very well said,' returned the lawyer,

01:39:32.481 --> 01:39:37.561
"'and whatever comes of it, I shall make it my business to see you are no loser.'

01:39:38.621 --> 01:39:42.441
"'There is an axe in the theatre,' continued Poole,

01:39:42.441 --> 01:39:45.161
"'and you might take the kitchen-poker for yourself.'

01:39:46.521 --> 01:39:52.061
The lawyer took that rude but weighty instrument into his hand and balanced it.

01:39:52.301 --> 01:39:55.941
"'Do you know, Poole,' he said, looking up,

01:39:55.941 --> 01:40:00.501
"'that you and I are about to place ourselves in a position of some peril?'

01:40:01.641 --> 01:40:05.681
"'You may say so, sir, indeed,' returned the butler.

01:40:06.401 --> 01:40:10.661
"'It is well, then, that we should be frank,' said the other.

01:40:10.661 --> 01:40:13.841
"'We both think more than we have said.

01:40:14.441 --> 01:40:16.661
Let us make a clean breast.

01:40:17.161 --> 01:40:21.361
This masked figure that you saw, did you recognize it?'

01:40:22.561 --> 01:40:27.081
"'Well, sir, it went so quick, and the creature was so doubled up,

01:40:27.181 --> 01:40:30.441
that I could hardly swear to it,' was the answer.

01:40:30.761 --> 01:40:34.321
"'But if you mean, was it Mr. Hyde?'

01:40:34.321 --> 01:40:37.441
"'Why, yes, I think it was.

01:40:37.441 --> 01:40:43.861
"'You see, it was much of the same bigness, and it had the same quick, light way with it,

01:40:44.061 --> 01:40:47.601
and then who else could have got in by the laboratory door?'

01:40:48.621 --> 01:40:54.321
"'You have not forgot, sir, that at the time of the murder he had still the key with him.

01:40:54.941 --> 01:40:56.521
But that's not all.'

01:40:57.701 --> 01:41:02.461
"'I don't know, Mr. Utterson, if you ever met this Mr. Hyde.'

01:41:02.461 --> 01:41:05.801
"'Yes,' said the lawyer, I once spoke with him.

01:41:05.801 --> 01:41:08.761
"'Then you must know, as well as the rest of us,

01:41:08.801 --> 01:41:14.241
that there was something queer about that gentleman, something that gave a man a turn.

01:41:14.941 --> 01:41:21.681
I don't know rightly how to say it, sir, beyond this, that you felt in your marrow

01:41:21.681 --> 01:41:23.861
kind of cold and thin.'

01:41:24.721 --> 01:41:29.641
"'I own I felt something of what you describe,' said Mr. Utterson.

01:41:30.061 --> 01:41:32.761
"'Quite so, sir,' returned Poole.

01:41:32.761 --> 01:41:36.481
"'Well, when that masked thing, like a monkey,

01:41:36.721 --> 01:41:42.601
jumped from among the chemicals and whipped into the cabinet, it went down my spine like ice.

01:41:43.341 --> 01:41:46.181
Oh, I know it's not evidence, Mr. Utterson.

01:41:46.541 --> 01:41:48.581
I'm book-learned enough for that.

01:41:48.981 --> 01:41:56.181
But a man has his feelings, and I give you my Bible word it was Mr. Hyde.'

01:41:56.181 --> 01:41:57.961
"'Ay, ay,' said the lawyer.

01:41:58.361 --> 01:42:01.141
My fears inclined to the same point.

01:42:01.781 --> 01:42:06.641
Evil, I fear, founded evil, was sure to come of that connection.

01:42:07.861 --> 01:42:09.841
Ay, truly I believe you.

01:42:10.021 --> 01:42:14.001
I believe poor Harry is killed, and I believe his murderer,

01:42:14.421 --> 01:42:19.801
for what purpose God alone can tell, is still lurking in his victim's room.

01:42:20.801 --> 01:42:22.981
Well, let our name be Vengeance.

01:42:23.901 --> 01:42:24.581
Call Bradshaw.'

01:42:25.681 --> 01:42:29.601
The footman came at the summons, very white and nervous.

01:42:30.241 --> 01:42:33.481
"'Put yourself together, Bradshaw,' said the lawyer.

01:42:33.741 --> 01:42:40.381
This suspense I know is telling upon all of you, but it is now our intention to make an end of it.

01:42:40.881 --> 01:42:44.501
Poole here and I are going to force our way into the cabinet.

01:42:45.361 --> 01:42:49.601
If all is well, my soldiers are broad enough to bear the blame.

01:42:50.541 --> 01:42:56.721
Meanwhile, lest anything should really be amiss, or any manufacture seek to escape by the back,

01:42:56.721 --> 01:43:00.961
you and the boy must go round the corner with a pair of good sticks,

01:43:01.141 --> 01:43:03.581
and take your post at the laboratory door.

01:43:04.361 --> 01:43:07.301
We give you ten minutes to get to your stations.'

01:43:08.261 --> 01:43:11.601
As Bradshaw left, the lawyer looked at his watch.

01:43:11.961 --> 01:43:16.341
"'And now, Poole, let us get to ours,' he said.

01:43:16.941 --> 01:43:21.061
And taking the poker under his arm led the way into the yard.

01:43:21.761 --> 01:43:26.201
The scud had banked over the moon, and it was now quite dark.

01:43:26.721 --> 01:43:31.361
The wind, which only broke in puffs and draughts into that deep well of building,

01:43:32.121 --> 01:43:35.781
tossed the light of the candle to and fro about their steps,

01:43:36.261 --> 01:43:41.721
until they came into the shelter of the theatre, where they sat down silently to wait.

01:43:42.561 --> 01:43:50.061
London hummed solemnly all around, but nearer at hand the stillness was only broken by the

01:43:50.061 --> 01:43:54.001
sounds of a footfall moving to and fro along the cabinet floor.

01:43:54.741 --> 01:43:59.001
"'So it will walk all day, sir,' whispered Poole.

01:43:59.281 --> 01:44:01.481
"'Ay, and the better part of the night,

01:44:01.981 --> 01:44:06.241
only when a new sample comes from the chemist as a bit of a break.

01:44:07.061 --> 01:44:11.381
Ah, it's an ill conscience that such an enemy to rest.

01:44:12.221 --> 01:44:17.241
Ah, sir, there's blood foully shed in every step of it.

01:44:17.641 --> 01:44:19.721
But hark again a little closer.

01:44:20.021 --> 01:44:23.981
Put your heart in your ears, Mr. Utterson, and tell me.'

01:44:24.001 --> 01:44:26.281
Is that the doctor's foot?'

01:44:27.221 --> 01:44:33.521
The steps fell lightly and oddly with a certain swing, for they all went so slowly.

01:44:34.161 --> 01:44:38.961
It was different indeed from the heavy creaking tread of Henry Jekyll.

01:44:40.101 --> 01:44:41.501
Utterson sighed.

01:44:42.181 --> 01:44:45.541
"'Is there never anything else?' he asked.

01:44:46.301 --> 01:44:47.541
Poole nodded.

01:44:47.981 --> 01:44:49.501
"'Once,' he said.

01:44:49.941 --> 01:44:52.261
"'Once I heard it weeping.'

01:44:53.301 --> 01:44:59.141
"'Weeping? How that?' said the lawyer, conscious of a sudden chill of horror.

01:45:00.461 --> 01:45:05.181
"'Weeping like a woman or a lost soul,' said the butler.

01:45:05.301 --> 01:45:10.091
"'I came away with that upon my heart that I could have wept to.'

01:45:11.741 --> 01:45:14.921
But now the ten minutes drew to an end.

01:45:15.341 --> 01:45:18.901
Poole disinterred the axe from under a stack of packing-straw.

01:45:18.901 --> 01:45:23.141
The candle was set upon the nearest table to light them to the attack,

01:45:23.561 --> 01:45:28.361
and they drew near with bated breath to where that patient foot was still

01:45:28.361 --> 01:45:32.661
going up and down, up and down, in the quiet of the night.

01:45:34.401 --> 01:45:39.361
"'Jekyll,' cried Utterson with a loud voice, "'I demand to see you.'

01:45:40.241 --> 01:45:44.141
He paused a moment, but there came no reply.

01:45:44.781 --> 01:45:49.181
"'I give you fair warning. Our suspicions are aroused,

01:45:49.501 --> 01:45:53.461
and I must and shall see you,' he resumed.

01:45:53.761 --> 01:45:56.721
"'If not by fair means, then by foul.

01:45:57.161 --> 01:46:00.861
If not by your consent, then by brute force.'

01:46:03.001 --> 01:46:07.281
"'Utterson,' said the voice, "'for God's sake, have mercy.'

01:46:08.661 --> 01:46:13.821
"'Ah, that's not Jekyll's voice, it's Hyde's,' cried Utterson.

01:46:14.141 --> 01:46:15.961
"'Down with the door, Poole!'

01:46:17.001 --> 01:46:21.641
Poole swung the axe over his shoulder. The blow shook the building,

01:46:22.001 --> 01:46:25.381
and the red bay's door leaped against the lock and hinges.

01:46:26.221 --> 01:46:31.561
A dismal screech, as of mere animal terror, rang from the cabinet.

01:46:32.361 --> 01:46:37.261
Up went the axe again, and again the panels crashed, and the frame bounded.

01:46:37.941 --> 01:46:41.941
Four times the blow fell, but the wood was tough,

01:46:41.941 --> 01:46:44.081
and the fittings were of excellent workmanship,

01:46:44.561 --> 01:46:47.821
and it was not until the fifth that the lock burst,

01:46:47.981 --> 01:46:50.761
and the wreck of the door fell inwards on the carpet.

01:46:52.181 --> 01:46:57.261
The besiegers, appalled by their own riots and the stillness that had succeeded,

01:46:57.821 --> 01:47:00.121
stood back a little and peered in.

01:47:00.761 --> 01:47:05.361
There lay the cabinet before their eyes in the quiet lamplight.

01:47:06.121 --> 01:47:09.121
A good fire glowing and chattering on the hearth,

01:47:09.121 --> 01:47:14.101
the kettle singing its thin strain, a drawer or two open,

01:47:14.381 --> 01:47:19.021
papers neatly set forth on the business table, and nearer the fire,

01:47:19.421 --> 01:47:24.441
the things laid out for tea. The quietest room, you would have said,

01:47:25.001 --> 01:47:30.921
and but for the glazed presses full of chemicals, the most commonplace that night in London.

01:47:31.841 --> 01:47:37.841
Right in the middle there lay the body of a man, sorely contorted and still twitching.

01:47:38.421 --> 01:47:46.081
They drew near on Tiptoe, turned it on its back, and beheld the face of Edward Hyde.

01:47:46.741 --> 01:47:52.361
He was dressed in clothes far too large for him, clothes of the doctor's bigness.

01:47:52.541 --> 01:47:58.961
The cords of his face still moved with a semblance of life, but life was quite gone.

01:47:59.361 --> 01:48:05.061
And by the crushed file in the hand, and the strong smell of kernels that hung upon the air,

01:48:05.061 --> 01:48:10.561
Utterson knew that he was looking on the body of a self-destroyer.

01:48:11.501 --> 01:48:17.001
We have come too late, he said sternly, whether to save or punish.

01:48:18.321 --> 01:48:24.741
Hyde is gone to his account, and it only remains for us to find the body of your master.

01:48:26.301 --> 01:48:30.161
The far greater proportion of the building was occupied by the theatre,

01:48:30.161 --> 01:48:36.281
which filled almost the whole ground story and was lighted from above, and by the cabinet,

01:48:36.581 --> 01:48:40.381
which formed an upper story at one end and looked upon the court.

01:48:41.301 --> 01:48:46.721
A corridor joined the theatre to the door on the by-street, and with this the cabinet

01:48:46.721 --> 01:48:53.581
communicated separately by a second flight of stairs. There were besides a few dark closets

01:48:53.581 --> 01:49:01.141
a spacious cellar. All these they now thoroughly examined. Each closet needed but a glance,

01:49:01.301 --> 01:49:07.921
for all were empty, and all, by the dust that fell from their doors, had stood long unopened.

01:49:08.421 --> 01:49:14.801
The cellar, indeed, was filled with crazy lumber, mostly dating from the times of the surgeon who

01:49:14.801 --> 01:49:21.421
was Jekyll's predecessor, but even as they opened the door they were advertised of the uselessness

01:49:21.421 --> 01:49:29.221
of further search by the fall of a perfect mat of cobweb which had for years sealed up the entrance.

01:49:30.401 --> 01:49:35.441
Nowhere was there any trace of Henry Jekyll, dead or alive.

01:49:36.981 --> 01:49:39.521
Poole stamped on the flags of the corridor.

01:49:39.841 --> 01:49:44.981
He must be buried here, he said, hearkening to the sound.

01:49:45.701 --> 01:49:51.921
Or he may have fled, said Utterson, and he turned to examine the door in the by-street.

01:49:52.321 --> 01:49:59.981
It was locked, and lying nearby on the flags they found the key, already stained with rust.

01:50:00.941 --> 01:50:04.761
This does not look like use, observed the lawyer.

01:50:05.661 --> 01:50:13.361
Use? echoed Poole. Do you not see, sir, it is broken, much as if a man had stamped on it.

01:50:14.241 --> 01:50:18.621
Ay, continued Utterson, and the fractures too are rusty.

01:50:19.701 --> 01:50:22.561
The two men looked at each other with a scare.

01:50:23.381 --> 01:50:28.941
This is beyond me, Poole, said the lawyer. Let us go back to the cabinet.

01:50:30.161 --> 01:50:36.521
They mounted the stair in silence, and still, with an occasional awestruck glance at the dead body,

01:50:37.081 --> 01:50:40.641
proceeded more thoroughly to examine the contents of the cabinet.

01:50:41.201 --> 01:50:47.901
At one table there were traces of chemical work, various measured heaps of some white salt being

01:50:47.901 --> 01:50:54.481
laid on glass saucers, as though for an experiment in which the unhappy man had been prevented.

01:50:55.481 --> 01:50:59.021
That is the same drug that I was always bringing him,

01:50:59.281 --> 01:51:05.701
said Poole, and even as he spoke, the kettle, with a startling noise, boiled over.

01:51:06.381 --> 01:51:11.421
This brought them to the fireside, where the easy-chair was drawn cozily up,

01:51:11.641 --> 01:51:17.041
and the tea-things stood ready at the sitter's elbow, the very sugar in the cup.

01:51:17.881 --> 01:51:23.821
There were several books on a shelf. One lay beside the tea-things open, and Utterson was

01:51:23.821 --> 01:51:30.621
amazed to find it a copy of a pious work, for which Jekyll had several times expressed a great

01:51:30.621 --> 01:51:36.581
esteem, annotated in his own hand with startling blasphemies.

01:51:37.701 --> 01:51:42.921
Next, in the course of their review of the chamber, the searchers came to the cheval glass,

01:51:43.481 --> 01:51:50.061
into whose depths they looked with an involuntary horror. But it was so turned as to show them

01:51:50.061 --> 01:51:56.281
nothing but the rosy glow playing on the roof, the fire sparkling in a hundred repetitions along

01:51:56.281 --> 01:52:03.221
the glazed front of the presses, and their own pale and fearful countenances stooping to look in.

01:52:04.201 --> 01:52:09.211
This glass has seen some strange things, sir," whispered Poole.

01:52:09.941 --> 01:52:14.881
And surely none stranger than itself, echoed the lawyer in the same tones.

01:52:15.121 --> 01:52:21.061
For what did Jekyll? He caught himself at the word with a start, and then,

01:52:21.061 --> 01:52:26.621
conquering the weakness, what did Jekyll want with it? He said,

01:52:27.021 --> 01:52:29.621
You may say that, said Poole.

01:52:30.921 --> 01:52:36.121
Next they turned to the business table. On the desk, among the neat array of papers,

01:52:36.461 --> 01:52:43.061
a large envelope was uppermost, and bore in the doctor's hand the name of Mr. Utterson.

01:52:43.781 --> 01:52:48.601
The lawyer unsealed it, and several enclosures fell to the floor.

01:52:49.361 --> 01:52:56.041
The first was a will, drawn in the same eccentric terms as the one which he had returned six months

01:52:56.041 --> 01:53:02.761
before, to serve as a testament in case of death, and as a deed of gift in case of disappearance.

01:53:03.681 --> 01:53:10.021
But in place of the name of Edward Hyde, the lawyer, with indescribable amazement,

01:53:10.021 --> 01:53:18.781
read the name of Gabriel John Utterson. He looked at Poole, and then back at the paper,

01:53:19.401 --> 01:53:24.061
and last of all at the dead malefactor stretched upon the carpet.

01:53:25.721 --> 01:53:32.481
My head goes round, he said. He has been all these days in possession.

01:53:33.161 --> 01:53:38.961
He had no cause to like me. He must have raged to see himself displaced,

01:53:38.961 --> 01:53:47.501
and he has not destroyed this document. He caught up the next paper. It was a brief note

01:53:47.501 --> 01:53:55.821
in the doctor's hand, and dated at the top. Oh, Poole! the lawyer cried. He was alive,

01:53:55.921 --> 01:54:03.921
and here this day. He cannot have been disposed of in so short a space. He must still be alive.

01:54:04.501 --> 01:54:14.361
He must have fled. And then why fled? And how? And in that case, can we venture to declare this

01:54:14.361 --> 01:54:22.721
suicide? Oh, we must be careful. I foresee that we may yet involve your master in some dire

01:54:22.721 --> 01:54:33.281
catastrophe. Why don't you read it, sir? asked Poole. Because I fear, replied the lawyer solemnly.

01:54:33.921 --> 01:54:42.221
God grant I have no cause for it. And with that he brought the paper to his eyes, and read as

01:54:42.221 --> 01:54:51.541
follows. My dear artisan, when this shall fall into your hands, I shall have disappeared. Under

01:54:51.541 --> 01:54:59.241
what circumstances I have not the penetration to foresee, but my instinct, and all the circumstances

01:54:59.241 --> 01:55:08.901
of my nameless situation, tell me that the end is sure, and must be early. Go then, and first read

01:55:08.901 --> 01:55:15.681
the narrative which Lanyon warned me he was to place in your hands, and if you care to hear more,

01:55:16.121 --> 01:55:23.001
turn to the confession of your unworthy and unhappy friend, Henry Jekyll.

01:55:24.281 --> 01:55:28.161
There was a third enclosure, asked artisan.

01:55:28.841 --> 01:55:36.441
Here, sir, said Poole, and gave into his hands a considerable packet, sealed in several places.

01:55:37.181 --> 01:55:45.481
The lawyer put it in his pocket. I would say nothing of this paper. If your master has fled,

01:55:45.481 --> 01:55:54.121
or is dead, we may at least save his credit. It is now ten. I must go home and read these

01:55:54.121 --> 01:56:00.781
documents in quiet. But I shall be back before midnight, when we shall send for the police.

01:56:03.021 --> 01:56:09.761
They went out locking the door of the theatre behind them, and artisan, once more leaving the

01:56:09.761 --> 01:56:16.201
gathered about the fire in the hall, trudged back to his office to read the two narratives

01:56:16.201 --> 01:56:20.701
in which the mystery was now to be explained.

01:56:22.841 --> 01:56:24.901
End of part three

01:56:35.383 --> 01:56:42.423
Part IV of The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.

01:56:58.063 --> 01:57:00.143
Doctor Lanyon's Narrative

01:57:02.623 --> 01:57:10.143
On the ninth of January, now four days ago, I received by the evening delivery a registered

01:57:10.143 --> 01:57:15.643
envelope addressed in the hand of my colleague and old school companion Henry Jekyll.

01:57:16.523 --> 01:57:22.423
I was a good deal surprised by this, for we were by no means in the habit of correspondence.

01:57:23.183 --> 01:57:29.043
I had seen the man dine with him indeed the night before, and I could imagine nothing

01:57:29.043 --> 01:57:33.023
in our intercourse that should justify formality of registration.

01:57:33.963 --> 01:57:39.803
The contents increased my wonder, for this is how the letter ran.

01:57:42.383 --> 01:57:43.583
Tenth December

01:57:44.563 --> 01:57:51.143
Dr. Lanyon, you are one of my oldest friends, and although we may have differed at times

01:57:51.143 --> 01:57:58.663
on scientific questions, I cannot remember, at least on my side, any break in our affection.

01:57:59.923 --> 01:58:07.143
There was never a day when, if you had said to me, Jekyll, my life, my honour, my reason

01:58:07.143 --> 01:58:13.283
depend upon you, I would not have sacrificed my left hand to help you.

01:58:14.283 --> 01:58:21.303
Lanyon, my life, my honour, my reason are all at your mercy.

01:58:22.023 --> 01:58:25.583
If you fail me to-night, I am lost.

01:58:27.043 --> 01:58:32.663
You might suppose, after this preface, that I am going to ask you for something dishonourable

01:58:32.663 --> 01:58:33.283
to grant.

01:58:34.223 --> 01:58:35.923
Judge for yourself.

01:58:37.203 --> 01:58:43.643
I want you to postpone all other engagements for to-night, by even if you were summoned

01:58:43.643 --> 01:58:49.723
to the bedside of an emperor, to take a cab, unless your carriage should be actually at

01:58:49.723 --> 01:58:55.923
the door, and with this letter in your hand for consultation, to drive straight to my

01:58:55.923 --> 01:58:56.483
house.

01:58:57.143 --> 01:58:59.463
Poole, my butler, has his orders.

01:58:59.923 --> 01:59:03.223
You will find him waiting your arrival with a locksmith.

01:59:03.723 --> 01:59:10.863
The door of my cabinet is then to be forced, and you are to go in alone, to open the glazed

01:59:10.863 --> 01:59:19.003
press, letter E, on the left hand, breaking the lock if it be shut, and to draw out, with

01:59:19.003 --> 01:59:25.963
all its contents as they stand, the fourth drawer from the top, or, which is the same

01:59:25.963 --> 01:59:28.143
thing, the third from the bottom.

01:59:28.923 --> 01:59:36.763
In my extreme distress of mind, I have a morbid fear of misdirecting you, but even if I am

01:59:36.763 --> 01:59:43.983
in error, you may know the right drawer by its contents, some powders, a file, and a

01:59:43.983 --> 01:59:44.743
paper book.

01:59:45.463 --> 01:59:52.583
This drawer I beg of you to carry back with you to Cavendish Square, exactly as it stands.

01:59:52.583 --> 01:59:58.263
This is the first part of the service, now for the second.

01:59:59.063 --> 02:00:05.243
You should be back if you set out at once on the receipt of this long before midnight,

02:00:05.863 --> 02:00:11.223
but I will leave you that amount of margin, not only in the fear of one of those obstacles

02:00:11.223 --> 02:00:16.963
that can neither be prevented nor foreseen, but because an hour when your servants are

02:00:16.963 --> 02:00:21.423
in bed is to be preferred for what will then remain to do.

02:00:22.363 --> 02:00:29.683
At midnight then, I have to ask you to be alone in your consulting room, to admit with

02:00:29.683 --> 02:00:36.763
your own hand into the house a man who will present himself in my name, and to place in

02:00:36.763 --> 02:00:40.983
his hands the drawer that you will have brought with you from my cabinet.

02:00:41.963 --> 02:00:47.443
Then you will have played your part, and earned my gratitude completely.

02:00:48.403 --> 02:00:55.023
Five minutes afterwards, if you insist upon an explanation, you will have understood that

02:00:55.023 --> 02:01:01.983
these arrangements are of capital importance, and that by the neglect of one of them, fantastic

02:01:01.983 --> 02:01:08.903
as they must appear, you might have charged your conscience with my death, or the shipwreck

02:01:08.903 --> 02:01:09.963
of my reason.

02:01:11.943 --> 02:01:18.643
Confident as I am that you will not trifle with this appeal, my heart sinks, and my hand

02:01:18.643 --> 02:01:21.643
trembles at the bare thought of such a possibility.

02:01:23.003 --> 02:01:29.643
Think of me at this hour in a strange place, laboring under a blackness of distress that

02:01:29.643 --> 02:01:37.503
no fancy can exaggerate, and yet well aware that, if you will but punctually serve me,

02:01:37.503 --> 02:01:41.803
my troubles will roll away like a story that is told.

02:01:42.663 --> 02:01:49.203
Serve me, my dear Lanyon, and save your friend, Henry Jekyll.

02:01:50.623 --> 02:01:56.163
P.S. I had already sealed this up when a fresh terror struck upon my soul.

02:01:56.983 --> 02:02:02.963
It is possible that the post-office may fail me, and this letter not come into your hands

02:02:02.963 --> 02:02:04.263
until to-morrow morning.

02:02:04.963 --> 02:02:11.343
In that case, dear Lanyon, do my errand when it shall be most convenient for you in the

02:02:11.343 --> 02:02:16.083
course of the day, and once more expect my messenger at midnight.

02:02:16.803 --> 02:02:25.443
It may then already be too late, and if that night passes without event, you will know

02:02:25.443 --> 02:02:29.263
that you have seen the last of Henry Jekyll.

02:02:33.123 --> 02:02:40.463
Upon reading of this letter I made sure my colleague was insane, but till that was proved

02:02:40.463 --> 02:02:45.623
beyond the possibility of doubt, I felt bound to do as he requested.

02:02:46.723 --> 02:02:52.003
The less I understood of this farrago, the less I was in a position to judge of its importance,

02:02:52.643 --> 02:02:57.803
and an appeal so worded could not be set aside without a grave responsibility.

02:02:58.723 --> 02:03:05.123
I rose accordingly from my table, got into a hansom, and drove straight to Jekyll's house.

02:03:05.943 --> 02:03:08.343
The butler was awaiting my arrival.

02:03:08.783 --> 02:03:13.303
He had received by the same post as mine a registered letter of instruction,

02:03:13.863 --> 02:03:17.363
and had sent at once for a locksmith and a carpenter.

02:03:18.243 --> 02:03:24.523
The tradesman came while we were yet speaking, and we moved in a body to old Dr. Denman's

02:03:24.523 --> 02:03:30.563
surgical theatre, from which, as you are doubtlessly aware, Jekyll's private cabinet

02:03:30.563 --> 02:03:32.603
is most conveniently entered.

02:03:33.223 --> 02:03:39.843
The door was very strong, the lock excellent, the carpenter avowed he would have great trouble

02:03:39.843 --> 02:03:46.723
and have to do much damage if force were to be used, and the locksmith was near despair.

02:03:47.283 --> 02:03:54.143
But this last was a handy fellow, and after two hours' work the door stood open.

02:03:54.523 --> 02:04:01.183
The press marked E was unlocked, and I took out the drawer, had it filled up with straw

02:04:01.183 --> 02:04:06.043
and tied in a sheet, and returned with it to Cavendish Square.

02:04:07.263 --> 02:04:10.223
Here I proceeded to examine its contents.

02:04:10.783 --> 02:04:16.963
The powders were neatly enough made up, but not with the nicety of the dispensing chemist,

02:04:17.323 --> 02:04:21.063
so that it was plain they were of Jekyll's private manufacture,

02:04:21.063 --> 02:04:26.423
and when I opened one of the wrappers I found what seemed to me a simple

02:04:26.423 --> 02:04:28.943
crystal and salt of a white colour.

02:04:29.883 --> 02:04:37.063
The file to which I next turned my attention might have been about half full of a blood red liquor,

02:04:37.583 --> 02:04:43.423
which was highly pungent to the sense of smell, and seemed to me to contain phosphorus

02:04:43.423 --> 02:04:45.663
and some volatile ether.

02:04:46.963 --> 02:04:50.163
At the other ingredients I could make no guess.

02:04:50.803 --> 02:04:56.183
The book was an ordinary version book, and contained little but a series of dates.

02:04:57.283 --> 02:05:00.043
These covered a period of many years,

02:05:00.343 --> 02:05:05.703
but I observed that the entries ceased nearly a year ago, and quite abruptly.

02:05:06.883 --> 02:05:12.343
Here and there a brief remark was appended to a date, usually no more than a single word,

02:05:13.103 --> 02:05:17.443
double occurring perhaps six times in a total of several hundred entries,

02:05:17.443 --> 02:05:23.983
and once very early in the list, and followed by several marks of exclamation,

02:05:24.763 --> 02:05:26.223
total failure.

02:05:27.943 --> 02:05:33.103
All this, though it whetted my curiosity, told me little that was definite.

02:05:33.643 --> 02:05:40.443
Here was a file of some sort, and the record of a series of experiments that had led,

02:05:40.843 --> 02:05:46.623
like too many of Jekyll's investigations, to no end of practical usefulness.

02:05:47.543 --> 02:05:53.623
How could the presence of these articles in my house affect either the honour, the sanity,

02:05:53.983 --> 02:05:56.603
or the life of my flighty colleague?

02:05:57.603 --> 02:06:01.983
If his messenger could go to one place, why could he not go to another?

02:06:02.623 --> 02:06:09.263
And even granting such impediment, why was this gentleman to be received by me in secret?

02:06:10.483 --> 02:06:16.223
The more I reflected, the more convinced I grew that I was dealing with a case of

02:06:16.223 --> 02:06:23.363
cerebral disease, and though I dismissed my servants to bed, I loaded an old revolver

02:06:23.363 --> 02:06:27.523
that I might be found in some posture of self-defence.

02:06:29.163 --> 02:06:32.383
Twelve o'clock had scarce brung out over London,

02:06:32.863 --> 02:06:36.323
ere the knocker sounded very gently on the door.

02:06:36.803 --> 02:06:43.783
I went myself at the summons, and found a small man crouching against the pillars of the portico.

02:06:44.603 --> 02:06:47.943
"'Are you from Dr. Jekyll?' I asked.

02:06:48.563 --> 02:06:54.543
He told me yes by a constrained gesture, and when I had bidden him enter,

02:06:54.803 --> 02:07:00.903
he did not obey me without a searching backward glance into the darkness of the square.

02:07:01.883 --> 02:07:08.383
There was a policeman not far off, advancing with his bullseye open, and at the sight,

02:07:08.983 --> 02:07:13.143
I thought my visitor started, and made greater haste.

02:07:13.783 --> 02:07:20.323
These particulars struck me, I confess, disagreeably, and as I followed him into

02:07:20.323 --> 02:07:25.443
the bright light of the consulting-room, I kept my hand ready on my weapon.

02:07:26.183 --> 02:07:29.763
Here, at last, I had a chance of clearly seeing him.

02:07:30.163 --> 02:07:33.863
I had never set eyes on him before, so much was certain.

02:07:34.643 --> 02:07:36.783
He was small, as I have said.

02:07:37.203 --> 02:07:41.303
I was struck besides with the shocking expression of his face,

02:07:41.303 --> 02:07:48.143
with this remarkable combination of great muscular activity, and great apparent debility

02:07:48.143 --> 02:07:56.343
of constitution, and last but not least with the odd subjective disturbance caused by his neighborhood.

02:07:57.563 --> 02:08:04.263
This bore some resemblance to incipient rigor, and was accompanied by a marked sinking of the pulse.

02:08:05.083 --> 02:08:10.443
At the time, I set it down to some idiosyncratic personal distaste,

02:08:10.443 --> 02:08:13.863
and merely wondered at the acuteness of the symptoms.

02:08:14.643 --> 02:08:20.663
But I have since had reason to believe the cause to lie much deeper in the nature of the man,

02:08:21.123 --> 02:08:25.363
and to turn on some nobler hinge than the principle of hatred.

02:08:26.643 --> 02:08:32.663
This person, who had thus from the first moment of his entrance struck in me what I can only

02:08:32.663 --> 02:08:40.063
describe as a disgustful curiosity, was dressed in a fashion that would have made an ordinary

02:08:40.063 --> 02:08:46.903
person laughable. His clothes, that is to say, although they were of rich and sober fabric,

02:08:47.283 --> 02:08:53.603
were enormously too large for him in every measurement, the trousers hanging on his legs,

02:08:53.863 --> 02:08:59.503
and rolled up to keep them from the ground, the waist of the coat below his hunches,

02:08:59.943 --> 02:09:03.063
and the collar sprawling wide upon his shoulders.

02:09:04.043 --> 02:09:11.443
Strange to relate, this ludicrous accoutrement was far from moving me to laughter. Rather,

02:09:11.703 --> 02:09:18.143
as there was something abnormal and misbegotten in the very essence of the creature that now faced me,

02:09:18.603 --> 02:09:26.063
something seizing, surprising, and revolting, this fresh disparity seemed but to fit in with

02:09:26.063 --> 02:09:32.983
and to reinforce it, so that, to my interest in the man's nature and character, there was added

02:09:32.983 --> 02:09:41.763
curiosity as to his origin, his life, his fortune and status in the world. These observations,

02:09:42.263 --> 02:09:48.663
though they have taken so great a space to be set down in, were yet the work of a few seconds.

02:09:49.383 --> 02:09:54.083
My visitor was indeed on fire with sombre excitement.

02:09:54.563 --> 02:10:01.723
Have you got it? he cried. Have you got it? And so lively was his impatience

02:10:01.723 --> 02:10:06.323
that he even laid his hand upon my arm and sought to shake me.

02:10:07.283 --> 02:10:13.603
I put him back, conscious at his touch of a certain icy pang along my blood.

02:10:14.503 --> 02:10:20.403
Come, sir, said I. You forgot that I have not yet the pleasure of your acquaintance.

02:10:20.403 --> 02:10:28.943
Be seated, if you please. Then I showed him an example, and sat down myself in my customary seat,

02:10:29.363 --> 02:10:35.243
and with as fair an imitation of my ordinary manner to a patient as the lateness of the hour,

02:10:35.603 --> 02:10:42.163
the nature of my preoccupations, and the horror I had of my visitor, would suffer me to muster.

02:10:43.043 --> 02:10:51.543
I beg your pardon, Dr. Lanyon, he replied, civilly enough. What you say is very well founded,

02:10:52.143 --> 02:10:55.443
and my impatience has shown its heels to my politeness.

02:10:56.523 --> 02:11:03.583
I came here at the instance of your colleague, Dr. Henry Jekyll, on a piece of business of

02:11:03.583 --> 02:11:11.583
some moment, and I understood. He paused and put his hand to his throat, and I could see,

02:11:11.583 --> 02:11:17.623
in spite of his collected manner, that he was wrestling against the approaches of the hysteria.

02:11:18.603 --> 02:11:24.983
I understood a drawer, but here I took pity on my visitor's suspense,

02:11:25.243 --> 02:11:28.303
and some perhaps on my own growing curiosity.

02:11:29.003 --> 02:11:33.423
There it is, sir, said I, pointing to the drawer,

02:11:33.743 --> 02:11:38.103
where it lay on the floor behind a table, and still covered with the sheet.

02:11:38.923 --> 02:11:44.243
He sprang to it, and then paused, and laid his hand upon his heart.

02:11:45.063 --> 02:11:49.243
I could hear his teeth grate with the convulsive action of his jaws,

02:11:49.683 --> 02:11:56.043
and his face was so ghastly to see, that I grew alarmed both for his life and reason.

02:11:57.123 --> 02:12:02.883
Compose yourself, said I. He turned a dreadful smile to me,

02:12:03.323 --> 02:12:07.823
and as if with the decision of despair, plucked away the sheet.

02:12:08.103 --> 02:12:16.263
At sight of the contents, he uttered one loud sob of such immense relief, that I sat petrified,

02:12:17.023 --> 02:12:21.683
and the next moment, in a voice that was already fairly well under control,

02:12:22.223 --> 02:12:26.243
have you a graduated glass? he asked.

02:12:27.623 --> 02:12:32.683
I rose from my place with something of an effort, and gave him what he asked.

02:12:33.623 --> 02:12:40.143
He thanked me with a smiling nod, measured out a few minims of the red tincture,

02:12:40.523 --> 02:12:47.663
and added one of the powders. The mixture, which was at first a reddish hue, began,

02:12:47.703 --> 02:12:53.743
in proportion as the crystals melted, to brighten in colour, to effervesce audibly,

02:12:54.123 --> 02:13:00.263
and to throw off small fumes of vapour. Suddenly, and at the same moment,

02:13:00.263 --> 02:13:08.403
the ebullition ceased, and the compound changed to a dark purple, which faded again more slowly

02:13:08.403 --> 02:13:16.303
to a watery green. My visitor, who had watched these metamorphoses with a keen eye, smiled,

02:13:16.823 --> 02:13:23.343
set down the glass upon the table, and then turned and looked upon me with an air of scrutiny.

02:13:24.423 --> 02:13:29.303
And now, said he, to settle what remains.

02:13:30.763 --> 02:13:39.923
Will you be wise? will you be guided? will you suffer me to take this glass in my hand,

02:13:39.963 --> 02:13:43.183
and to go forth from your house without further parley?

02:13:44.263 --> 02:13:51.223
Or has the greed of curiosity too much command of you? Think before you answer,

02:13:51.223 --> 02:14:00.383
for it shall be done as you decide. As you decide, you shall be left as you were before,

02:14:00.763 --> 02:14:07.523
and neither richer nor wiser, unless the sense of service rendered to a man in mortal distress

02:14:07.523 --> 02:14:15.343
may be counted as a kind of riches of the soul. Or, if you shall so prefer to choose,

02:14:15.343 --> 02:14:22.403
a new province of knowledge, a new avenue to fame and power, shall be laid open to you,

02:14:22.643 --> 02:14:31.063
here, in this room, upon the instant, and your sight shall be blasted by a prodigy to stagger

02:14:31.063 --> 02:14:39.303
the unbelief of Satan. Sir, said I, affecting a coolness that I was far from truly possessing,

02:14:39.963 --> 02:14:46.543
You speak enigmas, and you will perhaps not wonder that I hear you with no very strong

02:14:46.543 --> 02:14:52.683
impression of belief. But I have gone too far in the way of inexplicable services

02:14:52.683 --> 02:14:55.723
to pause before I see the end.

02:14:57.183 --> 02:15:04.923
It is well, replied my visitor. Lanyon, you remember your vows.

02:15:04.923 --> 02:15:15.563
What follows is under the seal of our profession. And now, you who have so long been bound to the

02:15:15.563 --> 02:15:23.043
most narrow and material views, you who have denied the virtue of transcendental medicine,

02:15:23.803 --> 02:15:28.803
you who have derided your superiors, behold.

02:15:29.923 --> 02:15:38.763
He put the glass to his lips, and drank at one gulp. A cry followed. He reeled, staggered,

02:15:38.983 --> 02:15:45.463
clutched at the table, and held on, staring with injected eyes, gasping with open mouth.

02:15:45.903 --> 02:15:55.003
And as I looked, there came, I thought, a change. He seemed to swell. His face became suddenly black,

02:15:55.003 --> 02:16:02.963
and the feature seemed to melt and alter. And the next moment I had sprung to my feet,

02:16:03.323 --> 02:16:09.343
and leaped back against the wall, my arms raised to shield me from that prodigy.

02:16:09.823 --> 02:16:12.683
My mind submerged in terror.

02:16:13.643 --> 02:16:25.763
O God! I screamed, and O God! again and again. For there, before my eyes, pale and shaken,

02:16:26.243 --> 02:16:32.983
and half fainting, and groping before him with his hands, like a man restored from death,

02:16:33.863 --> 02:16:37.643
there stood Henry Jekyll.

02:16:40.543 --> 02:16:49.783
What he told me in the next hour, I cannot bring my mind to set on paper. I saw what I saw,

02:16:50.203 --> 02:16:58.703
I heard what I heard, and my soul sickened at it. And yet, now when that sight has faded from my

02:16:58.703 --> 02:17:07.623
eyes, I ask myself if I believe it, and I cannot answer. My life is shaken to its roots.

02:17:07.623 --> 02:17:15.743
Sleep has left me. The deadliest terror sits by me at all hours of the day and the night,

02:17:16.023 --> 02:17:24.983
and I feel that my days are numbered. And then I must die, and yet I shall die incredulous.

02:17:25.963 --> 02:17:33.423
As for the moral turpitude that man unveiled to me, even with tears of penitence, I cannot,

02:17:33.423 --> 02:17:41.763
even in memory, dwell on it without a start of horror. I will say but one thing, Utterson,

02:17:42.463 --> 02:17:49.203
and that, if you can bring your mind to credit it, will be more than enough. The creature that

02:17:49.203 --> 02:17:57.443
crept into my house that night was on Jekyll's own confession, known by the name of Hyde,

02:17:57.443 --> 02:18:04.043
and hunted for in every corner of the land as the murderer of Coru.

02:18:06.543 --> 02:18:07.983
Hastey Lanyon

02:18:11.223 --> 02:18:13.483
End of part four

02:18:18.371 --> 02:18:25.211
Part 5 of The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.

02:18:39.691 --> 02:18:42.751
Henry Jekyll's Full Statement of the Case

02:18:45.531 --> 02:18:54.691
I was born to a large fortune, endowed besides with excellent parts, inclined by nature to

02:18:54.691 --> 02:19:01.111
industry, fond of the respect of the wise and good among my fellow men, and thus as

02:19:01.111 --> 02:19:07.271
might have been supposed, with every guarantee of an honorable and distinguished future.

02:19:07.271 --> 02:19:15.711
And indeed the worst of my faults was a certain impatient gaiety of disposition, such as has

02:19:15.711 --> 02:19:22.571
made the happiness of many, but such as I found it hard to reconcile with my imperious

02:19:22.571 --> 02:19:28.751
desire to carry my head high and wear a more than commonly grave countenance before the

02:19:28.751 --> 02:19:29.191
public.

02:19:30.451 --> 02:19:37.551
Hence it came about that I concealed my pleasures, and that when I reached years of reflection,

02:19:37.991 --> 02:19:42.691
and began to look round me and take stock of my progress and position in the world,

02:19:43.311 --> 02:19:49.071
I stood already committed to a profound duplicity of me.

02:19:50.371 --> 02:19:57.331
Many a man would have even blazoned such irregularities as I was guilty of, but from the high views

02:19:57.331 --> 02:20:04.451
that I had set before me, I regarded and hid them with an almost morbid sense of shame.

02:20:05.531 --> 02:20:12.131
It was thus rather the exacting nature of my aspirations, than any particular degradation

02:20:12.131 --> 02:20:19.211
in my faults, that made me what I was, and with an even deeper trench than in the majority

02:20:19.211 --> 02:20:26.671
of men, severed in me those provinces of good and ill which divide and compound man's dual

02:20:26.671 --> 02:20:27.191
nature.

02:20:28.471 --> 02:20:35.691
In this case, I was driven to reflect deeply and inveterate on that hard law of life which

02:20:35.691 --> 02:20:41.911
lies at the root of religion, and is one of the most plentiful springs of distress.

02:20:43.031 --> 02:20:47.931
Though so profound a double-dealer, I was in no sense a hypocrite.

02:20:48.331 --> 02:20:51.111
Both sides of me were in dead earnest.

02:20:51.891 --> 02:20:58.711
I was no more myself when I laid aside restraint and plunged in shame, than when I laboured

02:20:58.711 --> 02:21:04.611
in the eye of the day at the furtherance of knowledge or the relief of sorrow and suffering.

02:21:05.951 --> 02:21:12.531
And it chanced that the direction of my scientific studies, which led wholly towards the mystic

02:21:12.531 --> 02:21:18.811
and the transcendental, reacted and shed a strong light on this consciousness of the

02:21:18.811 --> 02:21:21.031
war among my members.

02:21:22.151 --> 02:21:28.391
With every day, and from both sides of my intelligence, the moral and the intellectual,

02:21:28.931 --> 02:21:36.191
I thus drew steadily nearer to that truth by whose partial discovery I have been doomed

02:21:36.191 --> 02:21:44.451
to such a dreadful shipwreck, that man is not truly one, but truly two.

02:21:45.231 --> 02:21:51.431
I say two, because the state of my own knowledge does not pass beyond that point.

02:21:52.751 --> 02:21:59.271
Others will follow, others will outstrip me on the same lines, and I hazard the guess

02:21:59.271 --> 02:22:07.111
that man will be ultimately known for a mere polity of multifarious, incongruous, and independent

02:22:07.111 --> 02:22:07.851
denizens.

02:22:07.851 --> 02:22:17.151
I, for my part, from the nature of my life, advanced infallibly in one direction, and

02:22:17.151 --> 02:22:18.731
in one direction only.

02:22:19.491 --> 02:22:26.811
It was on the moral side, and in my own person, that I learned to recognize the thorough and

02:22:26.811 --> 02:22:29.051
primitive duality of man.

02:22:29.791 --> 02:22:36.151
I saw that, of the two natures that contended in the field of my consciousness, even if

02:22:36.151 --> 02:22:43.031
I could rightly be said to be either, it was only because I was radically both, and

02:22:43.031 --> 02:22:48.811
from an early date, even before the course of my scientific discoveries had begun to

02:22:48.811 --> 02:22:55.671
suggest the most naked possibility of such a miracle, I had learned to dwell with pleasure,

02:22:56.071 --> 02:23:01.491
as a beloved daydream, on the thought of the separation of these elements.

02:23:02.231 --> 02:23:09.991
If each, I told myself, could be housed in separate identities, life would be relieved

02:23:09.991 --> 02:23:16.271
of all that was unbearable, the unjust might go his way, delivered from the aspirations

02:23:16.271 --> 02:23:22.991
and remorse of his more upright twin, and the just could walk steadfastly and securely

02:23:22.991 --> 02:23:29.731
on his upward path, doing the good things in which he found his pleasure, and no longer

02:23:29.731 --> 02:23:35.351
exposed to disgrace and penitence by the hands of this extraneous evil.

02:23:36.431 --> 02:23:43.931
It was the course of mankind that these incongruous faggots were thus bound together, that in

02:23:43.931 --> 02:23:50.531
the agonized womb of consciousness these polar twins should be continuously struggling.

02:23:51.651 --> 02:23:54.691
How then were they disassociated?

02:23:55.391 --> 02:24:03.031
I was so far in my reflections, when, as I have said, a side-light began to shine upon

02:24:03.031 --> 02:24:05.331
the subject from the laboratory table.

02:24:06.331 --> 02:24:13.811
I began to perceive more deeply than it has ever yet been stated the trembling immateriality,

02:24:14.091 --> 02:24:21.151
the mist-like transience, of this seemingly so solid body in which we walk attired.

02:24:21.971 --> 02:24:28.591
Certain agents I found to have the power to shake and pluck back that fleshly vestment,

02:24:29.151 --> 02:24:32.131
even as a wind might toss the curtains of a pavilion.

02:24:33.311 --> 02:24:40.211
For two good reasons I will not enter deeply into this scientific branch of my confession.

02:24:40.911 --> 02:24:47.271
First, because I have been made to learn that the doom and burden of our life is bound forever

02:24:47.271 --> 02:24:54.331
on man's shoulders, and when the attempt is made to cast it off, it but returns upon us

02:24:54.331 --> 02:24:57.411
with more unfamiliar and more awful pressure.

02:24:58.531 --> 02:25:07.191
Second, because as my narrative will make, alas, too evident, my discoveries were incomplete.

02:25:08.651 --> 02:25:15.511
Enough then that I not only recognized my natural body from the mere aura and effulgence

02:25:15.511 --> 02:25:23.071
of certain of the powers that made up my spirit, but managed to compound a drug by which these

02:25:23.071 --> 02:25:29.671
powers should be dethroned from their supremacy, and a second form and countenance substituted,

02:25:30.351 --> 02:25:36.731
none the less natural to me, because they were the expression and bore the stamp of

02:25:36.731 --> 02:25:38.851
lower elements in my soul.

02:25:39.851 --> 02:25:44.351
I hesitated long before I put this theory to the test of practice.

02:25:45.151 --> 02:25:53.051
I knew well that I risked death, for any drug that so potently controlled and shook the

02:25:53.051 --> 02:26:00.831
very fortress of identity might by the least scruple of an overdose, or at the least inopportunity

02:26:00.831 --> 02:26:07.271
in the moment of exhibition, utterly blot out that immaterial tabernacle which I looked

02:26:07.271 --> 02:26:08.631
to it to change.

02:26:09.531 --> 02:26:17.251
But the temptation of a discovery so singular and profound at last overcame the suggestions

02:26:17.251 --> 02:26:18.091
of alarm.

02:26:19.491 --> 02:26:22.271
I had long since prepared my tincture.

02:26:22.871 --> 02:26:29.331
I purchased at once, from a firm of wholesale chemists, a large quantity of a particular

02:26:29.331 --> 02:26:37.091
salt which I knew from my experiments to be the last ingredient required, and late one

02:26:37.091 --> 02:26:43.771
accursed night I compounded the elements, watched them boil and smoke together in the

02:26:43.771 --> 02:26:52.071
glass, and when the ebullition had subsided, with a strong glow of courage, drank off the

02:26:52.071 --> 02:26:52.471
potion.

02:26:54.091 --> 02:26:57.391
The most racking pangs succeeded.

02:26:58.471 --> 02:27:05.911
A grinding in the bones, deadly nausea, and a horror of the spirit that cannot be exceeded

02:27:05.911 --> 02:27:08.111
at the hour of birth or death.

02:27:09.491 --> 02:27:17.591
Then these agonies began swiftly to subside, and I came to myself as if out of a great

02:27:17.591 --> 02:27:18.271
sickness.

02:27:19.211 --> 02:27:25.771
There was something strange in my sensations, something indescribably new, and from its

02:27:25.771 --> 02:27:28.551
varied novelty incredibly sweet.

02:27:29.431 --> 02:27:33.131
I felt younger, lighter, happier in body.

02:27:33.691 --> 02:27:40.311
Within I was conscious of a heady recklessness, a current of disordered sensual images running

02:27:40.311 --> 02:27:48.331
like a mill-race in my fancy, a solution of the bonds of obligation, an unknown but not

02:27:48.331 --> 02:27:50.731
an innocent freedom of the soul.

02:27:52.031 --> 02:28:00.031
I knew myself, at the first breath of this new life, to be more wicked, tenfold more

02:28:00.031 --> 02:28:07.671
wicked, sold a slave to my original evil, and the thought in that moment braced and

02:28:07.671 --> 02:28:09.311
delighted me like wine.

02:28:10.291 --> 02:28:17.371
I stretched out my hands, exulting in the freshness of these sensations, and in the

02:28:17.371 --> 02:28:22.311
act I was suddenly aware that I had lost in stature.

02:28:23.331 --> 02:28:26.231
There was no mirror at that date in my room.

02:28:26.601 --> 02:28:32.071
That which stands beside me as I write was brought there later on, and for the very purpose

02:28:32.071 --> 02:28:33.451
of these transformations.

02:28:34.611 --> 02:28:38.231
The night, however, was far gone into the morning.

02:28:38.751 --> 02:28:43.971
The morning, black as it was, was nearly ripe for the conception of the day.

02:28:44.491 --> 02:28:51.111
The inmates of my house were locked in the most rigorous hours of slumber, and I determined,

02:28:51.111 --> 02:28:58.151
flush as I was with hope and triumph, to venture in my new shape as far as to my bedroom.

02:28:58.891 --> 02:29:04.851
I crossed the yard, wherein the constellations looked down upon me, I could have thought

02:29:04.851 --> 02:29:11.891
with wonder, the first creature of that sort that their unsleeping vigilance had yet disclosed

02:29:11.891 --> 02:29:12.391
to them.

02:29:12.951 --> 02:29:19.851
I stole through the corridors, a stranger in my own house, and coming to my room, I

02:29:19.851 --> 02:29:25.291
saw for the first time the appearance of Edward Hyde.

02:29:26.851 --> 02:29:33.991
I must here speak by theory alone, saying not that which I know, but that which I suppose

02:29:33.991 --> 02:29:35.411
to be most probable.

02:29:36.831 --> 02:29:43.611
The evil side of my nature, to which I had now transferred the stamping efficacy, was

02:29:43.611 --> 02:29:48.811
less robust and less developed than the good which I had just deposed.

02:29:49.631 --> 02:29:55.751
Again, in the course of my life, which had been, after all, nine-tenths a life of effort,

02:29:55.951 --> 02:30:03.191
virtue and control, it had been much less exercise and much less exhausted, and hence,

02:30:03.331 --> 02:30:09.951
as I think, it came about that Edward Hyde was so much smaller, slighter, and younger

02:30:09.951 --> 02:30:11.831
than Henry Jekyll.

02:30:11.831 --> 02:30:18.631
Even as good shone upon the countenance of the one, evil was written broadly and plainly

02:30:18.631 --> 02:30:19.991
on the face of the other.

02:30:21.111 --> 02:30:27.651
Evil besides, which I must still believe to be the lethal side of man, had left on that

02:30:27.651 --> 02:30:31.391
body an imprint of deformity and decay.

02:30:32.211 --> 02:30:39.891
And yet, when I looked upon that ugly idol in the glass, I was conscious of no repugnance,

02:30:39.891 --> 02:30:42.211
rather of a leap of welcome.

02:30:43.191 --> 02:30:45.331
This too was myself.

02:30:45.911 --> 02:30:48.171
It seemed natural and human.

02:30:48.711 --> 02:30:53.051
In my eyes it bore a livelier image of the spirit.

02:30:53.571 --> 02:31:00.011
It seemed more express and single than the imperfect and divided countenance I had been

02:31:00.011 --> 02:31:01.991
hitherto accustomed to call mine.

02:31:02.951 --> 02:31:08.531
And in so far as I was doubtless right, I have observed that when I wore the semblance

02:31:08.531 --> 02:31:15.351
of Edward Hyde, none could come near to me at first without a visible misgiving of the

02:31:15.351 --> 02:31:15.711
flesh.

02:31:16.811 --> 02:31:24.171
This, I take it, was because all human beings, as we meet them, are co-mingled out of good

02:31:24.171 --> 02:31:31.991
and evil, and Edward Hyde, alone in the ranks of mankind, was pure evil.

02:31:33.671 --> 02:31:36.291
I lingered but a moment at the mirror.

02:31:36.851 --> 02:31:40.031
The second and conclusive experiment had yet to be attempted.

02:31:40.651 --> 02:31:46.951
It yet remained to be seen if I had lost my identity beyond redemption, and must flee

02:31:46.951 --> 02:31:50.751
before daylight from a house that was no longer mine.

02:31:51.851 --> 02:31:58.271
And hurrying back to my cabinet, I once more prepared and drank the cup, once more suffered

02:31:58.271 --> 02:32:05.611
the pangs of disillusion, and came to myself once more with the character, the stature,

02:32:05.811 --> 02:32:08.351
and the face of Henry Jackall.

02:32:09.611 --> 02:32:13.291
That night I had come to the fatal crossroads.

02:32:14.311 --> 02:32:20.671
Had I approached my discovery in a more noble spirit, had I risked the experiment while

02:32:20.671 --> 02:32:27.971
under the empire of generous or pious aspirations, all must have been otherwise, and from these

02:32:28.251 --> 02:32:33.431
agonies of death and birth I had come forth an angel instead of a fiend.

02:32:34.351 --> 02:32:37.371
The drug had no discriminating action.

02:32:37.791 --> 02:32:40.851
It was neither diabolical nor divine.

02:32:41.671 --> 02:32:46.051
It but shook the doors of the prison-house of my disposition.

02:32:47.231 --> 02:32:53.831
And like the captives of Philippi, that which stood within ran forth.

02:32:53.831 --> 02:32:58.591
At that time my virtue slumbered.

02:32:58.851 --> 02:33:05.971
My evil, kept awake by ambition, was alert and swift to seize the occasion, and the thing

02:33:05.971 --> 02:33:08.911
that was projected was Edward Hyde.

02:33:09.591 --> 02:33:17.491
Hence, although I had now two characters as well as two appearances, one was wholly evil,

02:33:17.651 --> 02:33:24.971
and the other was still the old Henry Jackall, that incongruous compound of whose reformation

02:33:24.971 --> 02:33:28.571
and improvement I had already learned to despair.

02:33:29.871 --> 02:33:33.951
The movement was thus wholly toward the worse.

02:33:35.831 --> 02:33:41.751
Even at that time I had not conquered my aversions to the dryness of a life of study.

02:33:42.471 --> 02:33:48.191
I would still be merrily disposed at times, and as my pleasures were, to say the least,

02:33:48.411 --> 02:33:54.071
dignified, and I was not only well-known and highly considered, but growing towards the

02:33:54.071 --> 02:34:00.131
elderly man, this incoherency of my life was daily growing more unwelcome.

02:34:01.171 --> 02:34:07.391
It was on this side that my new power tempted me, until I fell in slavery.

02:34:08.111 --> 02:34:15.791
I had but to drink the cup to doff at once the body of the noted professor, and to assume,

02:34:16.011 --> 02:34:19.391
like a thick cloak, that of Edward Hyde.

02:34:20.291 --> 02:34:22.071
I smiled at the notion.

02:34:22.391 --> 02:34:29.011
It seemed to me at the time to be humorous, and I made my preparations with the most studious

02:34:29.011 --> 02:34:29.471
care.

02:34:30.351 --> 02:34:36.311
I took and furnished that house in Soho to which Hyde was tracked by the police, and

02:34:36.311 --> 02:34:42.591
engaged as a housekeeper a creature whom I knew well to be silent and unscrupulous.

02:34:43.531 --> 02:34:50.431
On the other side I announced to my servants that a Mr. Hyde, whom I described, was to

02:34:50.431 --> 02:34:57.311
have full liberty and power about my house in the square, and to parry mishaps I even

02:34:57.311 --> 02:35:01.711
called and made myself a familiar object in my second character.

02:35:02.511 --> 02:35:09.691
I next drew up that will to which you so much objected, so that if anything befell me in

02:35:09.691 --> 02:35:15.851
the person of Dr. Jekyll, I could enter on that of Edward Hyde without pecuniary loss,

02:35:16.771 --> 02:35:25.271
and thus fortified, as I supposed, on every side, I began to profit by the strange immunities

02:35:25.271 --> 02:35:26.551
of my position.

02:35:27.471 --> 02:35:34.291
Men have before hired bravos to transact their crimes, while their own person in reputation

02:35:34.291 --> 02:35:35.771
sat under shelter.

02:35:36.831 --> 02:35:40.591
I was the first that ever did so for his pleasures.

02:35:41.331 --> 02:35:47.431
I was the first that could plod in the public eye with a load of genial respectability,

02:35:47.951 --> 02:35:54.891
and in a moment, like a schoolboy, strip off these lendings and spring headlong into the

02:35:54.891 --> 02:35:55.871
sea of liberty.

02:35:56.831 --> 02:36:02.611
But for me, in my impenetrable mantle, the safety was complete.

02:36:03.351 --> 02:36:05.991
Think of it, I did not even exist.

02:36:06.811 --> 02:36:12.851
Let me but escape into my laboratory door, give me but a second or two to mix and swallow

02:36:12.851 --> 02:36:19.331
the draught that I had always standing ready, and whatever he had done, Edward Hyde would

02:36:19.331 --> 02:36:27.171
away like the stain of breath upon a mirror, and there in his stead, quietly at home, trimming

02:36:27.171 --> 02:36:34.071
the midnight lamp in his study, a man who could afford to laugh at suspicion would be

02:36:34.071 --> 02:36:35.511
Henry Jekyll.

02:36:37.671 --> 02:36:45.491
The pleasures which I made haste to seek in my disguise were, as I have said, undignified.

02:36:45.931 --> 02:36:53.191
I would scarce use a harder term, but in the hands of Edward Hyde they soon began to turn

02:36:53.191 --> 02:36:54.711
toward the monstrous.

02:36:55.211 --> 02:37:01.231
When I would come back from these excursions, I was often plunged into a kind of wonder

02:37:01.231 --> 02:37:03.391
at my vicarious depravity.

02:37:04.131 --> 02:37:10.031
This familiar that I called out of my own soul, and sent forth alone to do his good

02:37:10.031 --> 02:37:14.151
pleasure, was a being inherently malign and villainous.

02:37:14.711 --> 02:37:22.311
His every act and thought centred on self, drinking pleasure with bestial avidity from

02:37:22.311 --> 02:37:27.431
any degree of torture to another, relentless like a man of stone.

02:37:28.411 --> 02:37:35.191
Henry Jekyll stood at times aghast before the acts of Edward Hyde, but the situation

02:37:35.191 --> 02:37:40.971
was apart from ordinary laws, and insidiously relaxed the grasp of conscience.

02:37:40.971 --> 02:37:45.771
It was Hyde, after all, and Hyde alone that was guilty.

02:37:46.231 --> 02:37:47.831
Jekyll was no worse.

02:37:48.171 --> 02:37:54.371
He woke again to his good qualities, seemingly unimpaired, and he would even make haste where

02:37:54.371 --> 02:37:58.651
it was possible to undo the evil done by Hyde.

02:37:58.931 --> 02:38:02.651
And thus his conscience slumbered.

02:38:04.011 --> 02:38:10.311
Into the details of the infamy at which I was thus connived, for even now I can scarce

02:38:10.311 --> 02:38:14.491
grant that I committed it, I have no design of entering.

02:38:15.251 --> 02:38:22.431
I mean to point out the warnings and the successive steps with which my chastisement approached.

02:38:23.311 --> 02:38:30.291
I met with one accident, which, as it brought on no consequence, I shall no more than mention.

02:38:31.451 --> 02:38:39.011
An act of cruelty to a child aroused against me the anger of a passer-by, whom I recognized

02:38:39.011 --> 02:38:41.531
the other day in the person of your kinsman.

02:38:41.971 --> 02:38:44.851
The doctor and the child's family joined him.

02:38:45.331 --> 02:38:51.151
There were moments when I feared for my life, and at last, in order to pacify their too

02:38:51.151 --> 02:38:57.531
just resentment, Edward Hyde had to bring them to the door, and pay them in a cheque

02:38:57.531 --> 02:38:59.451
drawn in the name of Henry Jekyll.

02:39:00.411 --> 02:39:06.191
But this danger was easily eliminated from the future by opening an account at another

02:39:06.191 --> 02:39:13.471
name of Edward Hyde himself, and when, by sloping my hand backward, I had supplied my

02:39:13.471 --> 02:39:18.531
double with a signature, I thought I sat beyond the reach of fate.

02:39:19.931 --> 02:39:26.791
Some two months before the murder of Sir Danvers, I had been out for one of my adventures, had

02:39:26.791 --> 02:39:33.071
returned at a late hour, and woke the next day in bed with somewhat odd sensations.

02:39:33.071 --> 02:39:40.611
It was in vain I looked about me, in vain I saw the decent furniture and tall proportions

02:39:40.611 --> 02:39:47.871
of my room in the square, in vain that I recognized a pattern of the bed-curtains, and the design

02:39:47.871 --> 02:39:54.171
of the mahogany frame, something still kept insisting that I was not where I was, that

02:39:54.171 --> 02:40:00.891
I had not wakened where I seemed to be, but in the little room in Soho, where I was accustomed

02:40:00.891 --> 02:40:03.431
to sleep in the body of Edward Hyde.

02:40:04.411 --> 02:40:12.191
I smiled to myself, and in my psychological way began lazily to inquire into the elements

02:40:12.191 --> 02:40:19.291
of this illusion, occasionally, even as I did so, dropping back into a comfortable morning

02:40:19.291 --> 02:40:20.091
doze.

02:40:21.191 --> 02:40:28.751
I was still so engaged when, in one of my more wakeful moments, my eyes fell upon my

02:40:28.751 --> 02:40:29.331
hand.

02:40:30.531 --> 02:40:37.431
Now, the hand of Henry Jekyll, as you have often remarked, was professional in shape

02:40:37.431 --> 02:40:42.411
and size, it was large, firm, white, and comely.

02:40:43.111 --> 02:40:49.631
But the hand which I now saw, clearly enough in the yellow light of a mid-London morning,

02:40:50.191 --> 02:40:58.551
lying half shut on the bed-clothes, was lean, cordy, knuckly, of a dusky pallor, and thickly

02:40:58.551 --> 02:41:00.951
shaded with a swart growth of hair.

02:41:01.771 --> 02:41:05.171
It was the hand of Edward Hyde.

02:41:06.811 --> 02:41:12.211
I must have stared upon it for near half a minute, sunk as I was in the mere stupidity

02:41:12.211 --> 02:41:19.571
of wonder, before terror woke up in my breast as sudden and startling as the crash of cymbals,

02:41:19.831 --> 02:41:23.531
and bounding from my bed I rushed to the mirror.

02:41:24.211 --> 02:41:32.171
At the sight that met my eyes, my blood was changed into something exquisitely thin and

02:41:32.171 --> 02:41:32.591
icy.

02:41:34.011 --> 02:41:38.051
Yes, I had gone to bed Henry Jekyll.

02:41:38.631 --> 02:41:41.531
I had awakened Edward Hyde.

02:41:42.731 --> 02:41:44.911
How was this to be explained?

02:41:44.991 --> 02:41:46.131
I asked myself.

02:41:46.571 --> 02:41:51.171
And then, with another bound of terror, how was it to be remedied?

02:41:51.171 --> 02:41:57.931
It was well on in the morning, the servants were up, all my drugs were in the cabinet,

02:41:58.431 --> 02:42:04.851
a long journey down two pairs of stairs, through the back passage, across the open courts,

02:42:04.871 --> 02:42:10.871
and through the anatomical theatre, from where I was then standing horror-struck.

02:42:12.531 --> 02:42:19.451
It might indeed be possible to cover my face, but of what use was that, when I was unable

02:42:19.451 --> 02:42:22.311
to conceal the alteration in my stature?

02:42:23.211 --> 02:42:30.431
And then, with an overpowering sweetness of relief, it came back upon my mind that the

02:42:30.431 --> 02:42:34.171
servants were already used to the coming and going of my second self.

02:42:35.291 --> 02:42:42.031
I had soon dressed, as well as I was able, in clothes of my own size, had soon passed

02:42:42.031 --> 02:42:48.291
through the house, where Bradshaw stared and drew back at seeing Mr. Hyde at such an hour,

02:42:48.291 --> 02:42:55.051
and in such a strange array, and ten minutes later Dr. Jekyll had returned to his own

02:42:55.051 --> 02:43:01.631
shape and was sitting down, with a darkened brow, to make a faint of breakfasting.

02:43:03.891 --> 02:43:06.191
Small indeed was my appetite.

02:43:06.571 --> 02:43:18.271
This inexplicable incident, this reversal of my previous experience, seemed like the

02:43:18.271 --> 02:43:25.151
judgment, and I began to reflect more seriously than ever before on the issues and possibilities

02:43:25.151 --> 02:43:26.871
of my double existence.

02:43:27.831 --> 02:43:34.551
That part of me which I had the power of projecting, had lately been much exercised and nourished.

02:43:34.771 --> 02:43:40.751
It had seemed to me of late, as though the body of Edward Hyde had grown in stature,

02:43:41.171 --> 02:43:47.711
as though, before I wore that form, I were conscious of a more generous tide of blood,

02:43:48.251 --> 02:43:55.091
and I began to spy a danger, that if this were much prolonged, the balance of my nature

02:43:55.091 --> 02:44:01.771
might be permanently overthrown, the power of voluntary change be forfeited, and the

02:44:01.771 --> 02:44:06.251
character of Edward Hyde become irrevocably mine.

02:44:08.151 --> 02:44:13.011
The power of the drug had not been always equally displayed.

02:44:14.071 --> 02:44:18.491
Once, very early in my career, it had totally failed me.

02:44:18.931 --> 02:44:25.311
Since then I had been obliged, on more than one occasion, to double, and once with infinite

02:44:25.311 --> 02:44:27.851
risk of death, to treble the amount.

02:44:27.851 --> 02:44:35.151
And these rare uncertainties had cast hitherto the sole shadow on my contentment.

02:44:36.251 --> 02:44:43.591
Now, however, and in the light of that morning's accident, I was led to remark that, whereas

02:44:43.591 --> 02:44:49.711
in the beginning the difficulty had been to throw off the body of Jekyll, it had of late

02:44:49.711 --> 02:44:54.391
gradually but decidedly transferred itself to the other side.

02:44:54.391 --> 02:45:03.331
All things therefore seemed to point to this, that I was slowly losing hold of my original

02:45:03.331 --> 02:45:10.891
and better self, and becoming slowly incorporated with my second and worse.

02:45:13.531 --> 02:45:17.771
Between these two I now felt I had to choose.

02:45:18.411 --> 02:45:25.211
My two natures had memory in common, but all other faculties were most unequally shared

02:45:25.211 --> 02:45:26.231
between them.

02:45:26.751 --> 02:45:33.671
Jekyll, who was composite, now with the most sensitive apprehensions, now with a greedy

02:45:33.671 --> 02:45:37.811
gusto projected and shared in the pleasures and adventures of Hyde.

02:45:38.791 --> 02:45:45.951
But Hyde was indifferent to Jekyll, or but remembered him as the mountain bandit remembers

02:45:45.951 --> 02:45:49.031
the cavern in which he conceals himself from pursuit.

02:45:50.151 --> 02:45:56.371
Jekyll had more than a father's interest, Hyde had more than a son's indifference.

02:45:57.631 --> 02:46:04.171
To cast him my lot with Jekyll was to die to those appetites which I had long secretly

02:46:04.171 --> 02:46:07.331
indulged and had of late begun to pamper.

02:46:08.171 --> 02:46:15.811
To cast it in with Hyde was to die to a thousand interests and aspirations, and to become at

02:46:15.811 --> 02:46:20.111
the blow and for ever despised and friendless.

02:46:21.051 --> 02:46:27.331
The bargain might appear unequal, but there was still another consideration in the scales,

02:46:28.051 --> 02:46:34.171
for while Jekyll would suffer smartingly in the fires of abstinence, Hyde would not even

02:46:34.171 --> 02:46:36.311
be conscious of all that he had lost.

02:46:37.091 --> 02:46:43.931
Strange as my circumstances were, the terms of this debate are as old and commonplace

02:46:43.931 --> 02:46:44.771
as man.

02:46:44.771 --> 02:46:50.851
Much the same inducements and alarms cast the die for any tempted and trembling sinner,

02:46:51.351 --> 02:46:58.691
and it fell out with me as it falls with so vast a majority of my fellows, that I chose

02:46:58.691 --> 02:47:04.351
the better part, and was found wanting in the strength to keep to it.

02:47:05.191 --> 02:47:12.151
Yes I preferred the elderly and discontented doctor, surrounded by friends and cherishing

02:47:12.151 --> 02:47:18.971
honest hopes, and bade a resolute farewell to the liberty, the comparative youth, the

02:47:18.971 --> 02:47:26.111
light step, leaping impulses, and secret pleasures that I had enjoyed in the disguise of Hyde.

02:47:27.091 --> 02:47:33.631
I made this choice perhaps with some unconscious reservation, for I never gave up the house

02:47:33.631 --> 02:47:40.211
in Zoho, nor destroyed the clothes of Edward Hyde, which still lay ready in my cabinet.

02:47:40.991 --> 02:47:46.111
For two months, however, I was true to my determination.

02:47:46.891 --> 02:47:53.471
For two months I led a life of such severity as I had never before attained to, and enjoyed

02:47:53.471 --> 02:47:56.251
the compensations of an approving conscience.

02:47:57.371 --> 02:48:02.151
But time began at last to obliterate the freshness of my alarm.

02:48:02.511 --> 02:48:06.491
The praises of conscience began to grow into a thing of course.

02:48:06.981 --> 02:48:14.631
I began to be tortured with throws and longings, as of Hyde struggling after freedom, and at

02:48:14.631 --> 02:48:21.991
last, in an hour of moral weakness, I once again compounded and swallowed the transforming

02:48:21.991 --> 02:48:22.811
draught.

02:48:25.731 --> 02:48:31.911
I do not suppose that, when a drunkard reasons with himself upon his vice, he is once out

02:48:32.671 --> 02:48:38.771
times affected by the dangers that he runs through his brutish physical insensibility.

02:48:39.811 --> 02:48:45.391
Neither had I, long as I had considered my position, made enough allowance for the complete

02:48:45.391 --> 02:48:52.051
moral insensibility and insensate readiness to evil, which were the leading carriages

02:48:52.051 --> 02:48:53.671
of Edward Hyde.

02:48:54.491 --> 02:48:58.051
Yet it was by these that I was punished.

02:48:59.011 --> 02:49:02.091
My devil had long been caged.

02:49:02.651 --> 02:49:04.471
He came out roaring.

02:49:05.391 --> 02:49:12.171
I was conscious, even when I took the draught, of a more unbridled, more furious propensity

02:49:12.171 --> 02:49:12.871
to ill.

02:49:13.391 --> 02:49:19.931
It must have been this, I suppose, that stirred in my soul that tempest of impatience with

02:49:19.931 --> 02:49:23.791
which I listened to the civilities of my unhappy victim.

02:49:24.661 --> 02:49:32.491
I declare, at least, before God, no man morally sane could have been guilty of that crime

02:49:32.491 --> 02:49:38.811
upon so pitiful a provocation, and that I struck in no more reasonable spirit than that

02:49:38.811 --> 02:49:41.291
in which a sick child may break a plaything.

02:49:42.171 --> 02:49:49.131
But I had voluntarily stripped myself of all those balancing instincts by which even the

02:49:49.131 --> 02:49:56.711
of us continues to walk with some degree of steadiness among temptations, and in my case

02:49:56.711 --> 02:50:01.391
to be tempted, however slightly, was to fall.

02:50:02.751 --> 02:50:06.771
Instantly the spirit of hell awoke in me enraged.

02:50:07.071 --> 02:50:15.371
With a transport of glee I mauled the unresisting body, tasting delight from every blow, and

02:50:15.371 --> 02:50:21.671
it was not till weariness had begun to succeed that I was suddenly, in the top fit of my

02:50:21.671 --> 02:50:26.031
delirium, struck through the heart by a cold thrill of terror.

02:50:27.211 --> 02:50:29.011
A mist dispersed.

02:50:29.351 --> 02:50:36.891
I saw my life to be forfeit, and fled from the scene of these excesses, at once glorying

02:50:36.891 --> 02:50:44.691
and trembling, my lust of evil gratified and stimulated, my love of life screwed to the

02:50:44.691 --> 02:50:45.771
utmost peg.

02:50:46.991 --> 02:50:54.111
I ran to the house in Soho, and, to make assurance doubly sure, destroyed my papers.

02:50:54.991 --> 02:51:01.311
Hence I set out through the lamplit streets, in the same divided ecstasy of mind, gloating

02:51:01.311 --> 02:51:07.711
on my crime, light-headedly devising others in the future, and yet still hastening and

02:51:07.711 --> 02:51:10.811
still harkening in my wake for the steps of the Avenger.

02:51:11.551 --> 02:51:18.811
Hyde had a song upon his lips as he compounded the draught, and as he drank it pledged the

02:51:18.811 --> 02:51:19.611
dead man.

02:51:20.851 --> 02:51:28.111
The pangs of transformation had not done tearing him, before Henry Jekyll, with streaming tears

02:51:28.111 --> 02:51:34.271
of gratitude and remorse, had fallen upon his knees and lifted his clasped hands to

02:51:34.271 --> 02:51:34.631
God.

02:51:35.451 --> 02:51:40.431
The veil of self-indulgence was rent from head to foot.

02:51:41.071 --> 02:51:43.411
I saw my life as a whole.

02:51:44.071 --> 02:51:50.271
I followed it up from the days of my childhood, when I had walked with my father's hand, and

02:51:50.271 --> 02:51:57.431
through the self-denying toils of my professional life, to arrive again and again with the same

02:51:57.431 --> 02:52:01.491
sense of unreality at the damned horrors of the evening.

02:52:02.351 --> 02:52:05.151
I could have screamed aloud.

02:52:05.371 --> 02:52:11.491
I sought with tears and prayers to smother down the crowd of hideous images and sounds,

02:52:11.991 --> 02:52:19.291
with which my memory swarmed against me, and still, between the petitions, the ugly face

02:52:19.291 --> 02:52:22.371
of my iniquity stared into my soul.

02:52:23.211 --> 02:52:30.911
As the acuteness of this remorse began to die away, it was succeeded by a sense of joy.

02:52:31.711 --> 02:52:34.951
The problem of my conduct was solved.

02:52:35.771 --> 02:52:38.391
Hide was thenceforth impossible.

02:52:39.151 --> 02:52:44.731
Whether I would or not, I was now confined to the better part of my existence.

02:52:45.511 --> 02:52:49.611
And, oh, how I rejoiced to think of it!

02:52:49.871 --> 02:52:55.431
With what willing humility I embraced and knew the restrictions of natural life!

02:52:55.991 --> 02:53:02.691
With what sincere renunciation I locked the door by which I had so often gone and come,

02:53:03.331 --> 02:53:06.051
and ground the key under my heel!

02:53:08.451 --> 02:53:14.811
The next day came the news that the murder had not been overlooked, that the guilt of

02:53:14.811 --> 02:53:20.831
hide was patent to the world, and that the victim was a man high in public estimation.

02:53:21.391 --> 02:53:25.951
It was not only a crime, it had been a tragic folly.

02:53:26.971 --> 02:53:29.711
I think I was glad to know it.

02:53:29.891 --> 02:53:35.251
I think I was glad to have my better impulses thus buttressed and guarded by the terrors

02:53:35.251 --> 02:53:36.011
of the scaffold.

02:53:37.091 --> 02:53:40.091
Jekyll was now my city of refuge.

02:53:41.031 --> 02:53:47.931
Let but hide peep out an instant, and the hands of all men would be raised to take and

02:53:47.931 --> 02:53:48.651
slay him.

02:53:50.071 --> 02:53:54.751
I resolved in my future conduct to redeem the past.

02:53:55.371 --> 02:54:00.391
And I can say with honesty that my resolve was fruitful of some good.

02:54:00.391 --> 02:54:07.391
You know yourself how earnestly, in the last days of the last year, I laboured to relieve

02:54:07.391 --> 02:54:08.031
suffering.

02:54:08.651 --> 02:54:15.391
You know that much was done for others, and that the days passed quietly, almost happily

02:54:15.391 --> 02:54:16.411
for myself.

02:54:17.311 --> 02:54:22.091
Nor can I truly say that I wearied of this beneficent and innocent life.

02:54:22.711 --> 02:54:27.431
I think instead that I daily enjoyed it more completely.

02:54:27.431 --> 02:54:35.011
But I was still cursed with my duality of purpose, and as the first edge of my penitence

02:54:35.011 --> 02:54:44.851
wore off, the lower side of me, so long indulged, so recently chained down, began to growl for

02:54:44.851 --> 02:54:45.391
license.

02:54:46.171 --> 02:54:48.771
Not that I dreamed of resuscitating hide.

02:54:49.271 --> 02:54:53.111
The bare idea of that would startle me to frenzy.

02:54:53.751 --> 02:54:59.691
No, it was in my own person that I was once more tempted to trifle with my conscience,

02:55:00.271 --> 02:55:08.091
and it was as an ordinary secret sinner that I at last fell before the assaults of temptation.

02:55:09.891 --> 02:55:13.331
There comes an end to all things.

02:55:14.031 --> 02:55:21.791
The most capacious measure is filled at last, and this brief condescension to my evil finally

02:55:21.791 --> 02:55:24.631
destroyed the balance of my soul.

02:55:25.771 --> 02:55:28.191
And yet I was not alarmed.

02:55:28.671 --> 02:55:34.471
The fall seemed natural, like a return to the old days before I had made my discovery.

02:55:35.271 --> 02:55:42.571
It was a fine, clear January day, wet underfoot, where the frost had melted, but cloudless

02:55:42.571 --> 02:55:43.171
overhead.

02:55:44.351 --> 02:55:49.771
And the Regent's Park was full of winter churrupings, and sweet with spring odours.

02:55:50.571 --> 02:55:58.711
I sat in the sun on a bench, the animal within me licking the chops of memory, the spiritual

02:55:58.711 --> 02:56:05.511
side a little drowsed, promising subsequent penitence, but not yet moved to begin.

02:56:06.331 --> 02:56:14.371
After all, I reflected, I was like my neighbours, and then I smiled, comparing myself with other

02:56:14.371 --> 02:56:21.491
men, comparing my active goodwill with the lazy cruelty of their neglect, and at the

02:56:21.491 --> 02:56:29.011
very moment of that vain glorious thought a qualm came over me, a horrid nausea, and

02:56:29.011 --> 02:56:31.211
the most deadly shuddering.

02:56:32.711 --> 02:56:41.411
These passed away and left me faint, and then as in its turn faintness subsided.

02:56:42.691 --> 02:56:49.711
I began to be aware of a change in the temper of my thoughts, a greater boldness, a contempt

02:56:49.711 --> 02:56:54.451
of danger, a solution of the bonds of obligation.

02:56:55.291 --> 02:56:56.691
I looked down.

02:56:57.571 --> 02:57:04.531
My clothes hung formlessly on my shrunken limbs, the hand that lay on my knee was corded

02:57:04.531 --> 02:57:05.191
and hairy.

02:57:05.951 --> 02:57:09.491
I was once more Edward Hyde.

02:57:10.471 --> 02:57:16.871
A moment before I had been safe of all men's respect, wealthy, beloved, the cloth laying

02:57:16.871 --> 02:57:24.771
from me in the dining-room at home, and now I was the common quarry of mankind, hunted,

02:57:25.211 --> 02:57:29.131
homeless, a known murderer, thrall to the gallows.

02:57:30.391 --> 02:57:34.631
My reason wavered, but it did not fail me utterly.

02:57:35.091 --> 02:57:41.831
I have more than once observed that in my second character my faculties seemed sharpened

02:57:41.831 --> 02:57:45.771
to a point, and my spirits more tensely elastic.

02:57:46.671 --> 02:57:53.371
Thus it came about that, where Jekyll perhaps might have succumbed, Hyde rose to the importance

02:57:53.371 --> 02:57:54.171
of the moment.

02:57:55.071 --> 02:57:58.611
My drugs were in one of the presses of my cabinet.

02:57:59.291 --> 02:58:01.251
How was I to reach them?

02:58:01.251 --> 02:58:08.311
That was the problem that, crushing my temples in my hands, I set myself to solve.

02:58:09.531 --> 02:58:11.731
The laboratory door I had closed.

02:58:12.291 --> 02:58:17.931
If I sought to enter by the house, my own servants would consign me to the gallows.

02:58:18.651 --> 02:58:23.691
I saw I must employ another hand, and thought of Lanyon.

02:58:24.411 --> 02:58:26.091
How was he to be reached?

02:58:26.191 --> 02:58:27.071
How persuaded?

02:58:27.711 --> 02:58:33.571
Supposing that I escaped capture in the streets, how was I to make my way into his presence?

02:58:34.251 --> 02:58:41.431
How should I, an unknown and displeasing visitor, prevail on the famous physician to rifle the

02:58:41.431 --> 02:58:43.851
study of his colleague Dr. Jekyll?

02:58:45.451 --> 02:58:51.711
Then I remembered that of my original character one part remained to me.

02:58:52.131 --> 02:58:59.611
I could write my own hand, and once I had conceived that kindling spark, the way that

02:58:59.611 --> 02:59:03.791
I must follow became lighted up from end to end.

02:59:05.211 --> 02:59:11.531
Thereupon I arranged my clothes as best I could, and summoning a passing handsome, drove

02:59:11.531 --> 02:59:16.831
to an hotel in Portland Street, the name of which I chanced to remember.

02:59:17.711 --> 02:59:23.591
At my appearance, which was indeed comical enough, however tragic a fate these garments

02:59:23.591 --> 02:59:27.411
covered, the driver could not conceal his mirth.

02:59:27.791 --> 02:59:34.031
I gnashed my teeth upon him with a gust of devilish fury, and the smile withered from

02:59:34.031 --> 02:59:34.931
his face.

02:59:35.471 --> 02:59:42.511
Happily for him, yet more happily for myself, for in another instant I had certainly dragged

02:59:42.511 --> 02:59:43.931
him from his perch.

02:59:44.851 --> 02:59:52.531
At the inn, as I entered, I looked about me with so black a countenance as made the attendants

02:59:52.531 --> 02:59:53.251
tremble.

02:59:54.131 --> 03:00:01.471
Not a look did they exchange in my presence, but obsequiously took my orders, led me to

03:00:01.471 --> 03:00:05.271
a private room, and brought me wherewithal to write.

03:00:06.311 --> 03:00:13.611
Hyde, in danger of his life, was a creature new to me, shaken with inordinate anger, strung

03:00:13.611 --> 03:00:17.851
to the pitch of murder, lusting to inflict pain.

03:00:18.851 --> 03:00:25.191
Yet the creature was astute, mastered his fury with a great effort of the will, composed

03:00:25.191 --> 03:00:32.331
his two important letters, one to Lanyon and one to Poole, and that he might receive actual

03:00:32.331 --> 03:00:37.751
evidence of their being posted, sent them out with directions that they should be registered.

03:00:38.931 --> 03:00:45.111
Thenceforward he sat all day over the fire in the private room, gnawing his nails.

03:00:45.891 --> 03:00:52.311
There he dined, sitting alone with his fears, the waiter visibly quailing before his eye,

03:00:52.671 --> 03:00:58.871
and thence, when the night was fully come, he set forth in the corner of a closed cab,

03:00:59.371 --> 03:01:02.931
and was driven to and fro about the streets of the city.

03:01:05.111 --> 03:01:12.971
He—I say I cannot say I—that child of hell had nothing human, nothing lived in him

03:01:12.971 --> 03:01:20.351
but fear and hatred, and when at last, thinking the driver had begun to grow suspicious, he

03:01:20.351 --> 03:01:27.511
discharged the cab and ventured on foot, attired in his misfitting clothes, an object marked

03:01:27.511 --> 03:01:35.111
for observation, into the midst of the nocturnal passengers, these two base passions raged

03:01:35.111 --> 03:01:37.031
within him like a tempest.

03:01:38.051 --> 03:01:44.531
He walked fast, hunted by his fears, chattering to himself, skulking through the less frequented

03:01:44.531 --> 03:01:49.291
thoroughfares, counting the minutes that still divided him from midnight.

03:01:50.271 --> 03:01:54.151
Once a woman spoke to him, offering, I think, a box of lights.

03:01:54.151 --> 03:01:58.651
He smote her in the face, and she fled.

03:02:00.151 --> 03:02:07.371
When I came to myself at Lanyon's, the horror of my old friend perhaps affected me somewhat.

03:02:08.191 --> 03:02:09.531
I do not know.

03:02:10.171 --> 03:02:14.991
It was at least but a drop in the sea to the abhorrence with which I looked back upon these

03:02:14.991 --> 03:02:15.471
hours.

03:02:16.311 --> 03:02:18.111
A change had come over me.

03:02:18.111 --> 03:02:21.111
It was no longer the fear of the gallows.

03:02:21.511 --> 03:02:24.931
It was the horror of being hide that wracked me.

03:02:25.531 --> 03:02:29.651
I received Lanyon's condemnation partly in a dream.

03:02:30.251 --> 03:02:34.591
It was partly in a dream that I came home to my own house and got into bed.

03:02:35.531 --> 03:02:42.891
I slept after the prostration of the day with a stringent and profound slumber, which not

03:02:42.891 --> 03:02:46.211
even the nightmares that wrung me could avail to break.

03:02:47.131 --> 03:02:51.871
I woke in the morning shaken, weakened, but refreshed.

03:02:52.451 --> 03:02:57.951
I still hated and feared the thought of the brute that slept within me.

03:02:58.511 --> 03:03:04.851
And I had not, of course, forgotten the apolic dangers of the day before, but I was once

03:03:04.851 --> 03:03:12.371
more at home, in my own house, and close to my drugs, and gratitude for my escape, shone

03:03:12.371 --> 03:03:17.231
so strong in my soul that it almost rivaled the brightness of hope.

03:03:18.711 --> 03:03:24.511
I was stepping leisurely across the court after breakfast, drinking the chill of the

03:03:24.511 --> 03:03:32.291
air with pleasure, when I was seized again with those indescribable sensations that heralded

03:03:32.291 --> 03:03:33.111
the change.

03:03:33.771 --> 03:03:39.831
And I had but the time to gain the shelter of my cabinet before I was once again raging

03:03:39.831 --> 03:03:42.591
and freezing with the passions of hide.

03:03:43.911 --> 03:03:52.671
It took on this occasion a double dose to recall me to myself, and, alas, six hours

03:03:52.671 --> 03:04:00.351
after, as I sat looking sadly in the fire, the pangs returned, and the drug had to be

03:04:00.351 --> 03:04:01.011
re-administered.

03:04:01.991 --> 03:04:09.751
In short, from that day forth it seemed only by great effort as of gymnastics, and only

03:04:09.751 --> 03:04:15.491
under the immediate stimulation of the drug, that I was able to wear the countenance of

03:04:15.491 --> 03:04:15.951
juggle.

03:04:16.891 --> 03:04:23.051
At all hours of the day and night I would be taken with a premonitory shudder.

03:04:23.291 --> 03:04:30.391
Above all, if I slept, or even dozed for a moment in my chair, it was always as hide

03:04:30.391 --> 03:04:31.551
that I awakened.

03:04:32.611 --> 03:04:39.111
Under the strain of this continually impending doom, and by the sleeplessness to which I

03:04:39.111 --> 03:04:46.891
now condemned myself, ay, even beyond what I had thought possible to man, I became in

03:04:46.891 --> 03:04:55.911
my own person a creature eaten up and emptied by fever, languidly weak both in body and

03:04:55.911 --> 03:05:01.951
mind, and solely occupied by one thought of my other self.

03:05:02.931 --> 03:05:10.291
But when I slept, or when the virtue of the medicine wore off, I would leap almost without

03:05:10.291 --> 03:05:16.271
transition, for the pangs of transformation grew daily less marked, into the possession

03:05:16.271 --> 03:05:23.431
of a fancy brimming with images of terror, a soul boiling with causeless hatreds, and

03:05:23.431 --> 03:05:28.771
a body that seemed not strong enough to contain the raging energies of life.

03:05:29.601 --> 03:05:36.731
The powers of hide seemed to have grown with the sickliness of juggle, and certainly the

03:05:36.731 --> 03:05:40.491
hate that now divided them was equal on each side.

03:05:40.931 --> 03:05:43.991
With juggle it was a thing of vital instinct.

03:05:44.431 --> 03:05:50.171
He now had seen the full deformity of that creature that shared with him some of the

03:05:50.171 --> 03:05:57.211
phenomena of consciousness, and was co-heir with him to death, and beyond these links

03:05:57.211 --> 03:06:02.751
of community, which in themselves made the most poignant part of his distress, he thought

03:06:02.751 --> 03:06:10.331
of hide, for all his energy of life, as of something not only hellish, but inorganic.

03:06:11.151 --> 03:06:17.431
This was the shocking thing, that the slime of the pit seemed to utter cries and voices,

03:06:18.031 --> 03:06:25.651
that the amorphous dust gesticulated and sinned, that what was dead and had no shape should

03:06:25.651 --> 03:06:28.511
usurp the offices of life.

03:06:29.571 --> 03:06:37.591
And this again, that that insurgent horror was knit to him closer than a wife, closer

03:06:37.591 --> 03:06:43.831
than an eye, lay caged in his flesh, where he heard it mutter and felt it struggle to

03:06:43.831 --> 03:06:51.491
be born, and at every hour of weakness, and in the confidence of slumber, prevailed against

03:06:51.911 --> 03:06:54.691
and deposed him out of life.

03:06:56.171 --> 03:06:59.671
The hatred of hide for juggle was of a different colour.

03:07:00.471 --> 03:07:06.931
His terror of the gallows drove him continually to commit temporary suicide, and return to

03:07:06.931 --> 03:07:10.631
his subordinate station of a part instead of a person.

03:07:11.431 --> 03:07:17.211
But he loathed the necessity, he loathed the despondency into which juggle was now fallen,

03:07:17.211 --> 03:07:21.911
and he resented the dislike with which he was himself regarded.

03:07:22.691 --> 03:07:28.991
Hence the ape-like tricks that he would play me, scrawling in my own hand blasphemies on

03:07:28.991 --> 03:07:34.131
the pages of my books, burning the letters and destroying the portraits of my father,

03:07:34.691 --> 03:07:41.291
and indeed, had it not been for his fear of death, he would long ago have ruined himself

03:07:41.291 --> 03:07:44.291
in order to involve me in the ruin.

03:07:45.091 --> 03:07:48.371
But his love of me is wonderful.

03:07:48.931 --> 03:07:50.091
I go further.

03:07:50.631 --> 03:07:56.751
I, who sicken and freeze at the mere thought of him, when I recall the abjection and passion

03:07:56.751 --> 03:08:02.471
of this attachment, and when I know how he fears my power to cut him off by suicide,

03:08:03.211 --> 03:08:06.811
I find it in my heart to pity him.

03:08:07.991 --> 03:08:14.891
It is useless, and the time awfully fails me, to prolong this description.

03:08:15.771 --> 03:08:18.851
No one has ever suffered such torments.

03:08:19.671 --> 03:08:28.551
Let that suffice, and yet even to these habit brought no, not alleviation, but a certain

03:08:28.551 --> 03:08:35.311
callousness of soul, a certain acquiescence of despair, and my punishment might have gone

03:08:35.311 --> 03:08:42.971
for years, but for the last calamity which has now fallen, and which has finally severed

03:08:42.971 --> 03:08:45.471
me from my own face and nature.

03:08:47.051 --> 03:08:52.971
My provision of the salts, which had never been renewed since the date of the first experiment,

03:08:53.631 --> 03:08:54.931
began to run low.

03:08:55.451 --> 03:08:59.091
I sent out for a fresh supply, and mixed the draft.

03:08:59.751 --> 03:09:03.091
The ebullition followed, and the first change of colour.

03:09:03.731 --> 03:09:05.071
Not the second.

03:09:06.331 --> 03:09:10.331
I drank it, and it was without efficiency.

03:09:11.871 --> 03:09:15.991
You will learn from Poole how I have had London ransacked.

03:09:17.031 --> 03:09:25.431
It was in vain, and I am now persuaded that my first supply was impure, and that it was

03:09:25.431 --> 03:09:30.371
that unknown impurity which lent efficacy to the draft.

03:09:33.051 --> 03:09:39.191
About a week has passed, and I am now finishing this statement under the influence of the

03:09:39.191 --> 03:09:40.911
last of the old powders.

03:09:41.871 --> 03:09:49.551
This then is the last time, short of a miracle, that Henry Jekyll can think his own thoughts,

03:09:49.551 --> 03:09:51.351
or see his own face.

03:09:51.991 --> 03:09:55.351
Now how sadly altered! in the glass!

03:09:56.191 --> 03:10:02.631
Nor must I delay too long to bring my writing to an end, for if my narrative has hitherto

03:10:02.631 --> 03:10:09.211
escape destruction, it has been by a combination of great prudence and great good luck.

03:10:09.891 --> 03:10:15.631
Should the throes of change take me in the act of writing it, I will tear it in pieces.

03:10:16.351 --> 03:10:22.831
But if some time shall have elapsed after I have laid it by, his wonderful selfishness

03:10:22.831 --> 03:10:28.831
and circumscription to the moment will probably save it once again from the action of his

03:10:28.831 --> 03:10:30.131
ape-like spite.

03:10:31.391 --> 03:10:38.051
And indeed the doom that is closing on us both has already changed and crushed him.

03:10:38.611 --> 03:10:45.431
Half an hour from now, when I shall again and for ever re-endue that hated personality,

03:10:46.271 --> 03:10:54.731
I know how I shall sit shuddering and weeping in my chair, or continue, with the most strained

03:10:54.731 --> 03:11:01.631
and fear-struck ecstasy of listening, to pace up and down this room, my last earthly

03:11:01.631 --> 03:11:06.531
refuge, and give ear to every sound of menace.

03:11:07.411 --> 03:11:14.571
Will Hyde die upon the scaffold, or will he find courage to release himself at the last

03:11:14.571 --> 03:11:15.091
moment?

03:11:16.511 --> 03:11:17.751
God knows!

03:11:18.251 --> 03:11:19.611
I am careless.

03:11:20.391 --> 03:11:26.511
This is my true hour of death, concerns another than myself.

03:11:27.711 --> 03:11:35.691
Here then, as I lay down the pen and proceed to seal up my confession, I bring the life

03:11:35.691 --> 03:11:40.411
of that unhappy Henry Jekyll to an end.

03:11:43.131 --> 03:11:48.431
End of the strange case of Doctor Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.
